00:04:56.380 --> 00:04:56.910
All right.

00:04:56.910 --> 00:04:58.701
So there's lots of
different ways to do it.

00:04:58.701 --> 00:05:02.240
And ideally, I don't screw this
up in front of all of you guys

00:05:02.240 --> 00:05:03.360
right now.

00:05:03.360 --> 00:05:06.510
But so really, a cool
trick is-- we always

00:05:06.510 --> 00:05:09.806
try to soft-cook eggs
for our porridge.

00:05:09.806 --> 00:05:11.680
We're going to make a
Westlake rice porridge.

00:05:11.680 --> 00:05:13.180
So the idea behind
this whole thing

00:05:13.180 --> 00:05:17.750
is Westlake beef soup is a
really classic Cantonese, kind

00:05:17.750 --> 00:05:19.640
of Chinese American
dish that I've

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:22.060
had at lots of
places, specifically

00:05:22.060 --> 00:05:24.410
R&amp;G Lounge, which is one
of my favorite restaurants

00:05:24.410 --> 00:05:25.840
in the entire universe.

00:05:25.840 --> 00:05:30.127
But what it is is kind
of like an egg drop soup,

00:05:30.127 --> 00:05:30.960
but there's no yolk.

00:05:30.960 --> 00:05:34.890
It's basically an
egg white soup that's

00:05:34.890 --> 00:05:36.400
thickened with corn
starch, usually.

00:05:36.400 --> 00:05:38.800
It's got some stock in it.

00:05:38.800 --> 00:05:42.950
And there's always beef,
cilantro, and sometimes

00:05:42.950 --> 00:05:45.000
there's imitation
crab or real crab.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:48.170
So the idea of
this whole dish was

00:05:48.170 --> 00:05:50.490
we wanted to make a dish
at Mission Chinese that

00:05:50.490 --> 00:05:53.725
wasn't like a corn-starch
thick, slurried soup.

00:05:53.725 --> 00:05:56.350
We wanted to make something that
had the same kind of feeling--

00:05:56.350 --> 00:06:00.640
mouth-feel, texture-- as hot
and sour soup or egg drop soup

00:06:00.640 --> 00:06:04.480
or chicken and corn soup, but
not using the corn starch.

00:06:04.480 --> 00:06:07.882
So for me, congee has always
been a really awesome--

00:06:07.882 --> 00:06:09.590
how many people here
know what congee is?

00:06:09.590 --> 00:06:10.830
I'm sure a lot of you.

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:13.100
So usually, congee is--
depending on where you go,

00:06:13.100 --> 00:06:14.900
it's very thick and very tight.

00:06:14.900 --> 00:06:17.940
You usually eat it in the
morning for breakfast, or I do.

00:06:17.940 --> 00:06:19.840
And it gets you going
through the day.

00:06:19.840 --> 00:06:21.265
And you're not
hungry for a while.

00:06:21.265 --> 00:06:23.140
But at the restaurant,
what we were seeing is

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:24.609
we would make this
rice porridge.

00:06:24.609 --> 00:06:26.150
And people would
just get crushed off

00:06:26.150 --> 00:06:27.480
of a bowl of rice porridge.

00:06:27.480 --> 00:06:30.500
And they wouldn't be able
to eat anything else.

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:32.980
And you would also
just be losing money.

00:06:32.980 --> 00:06:36.510
Because how much can you charge
for a bowl of rice and water?

00:06:36.510 --> 00:06:39.977
So in grand Mission
Chinese style,

00:06:39.977 --> 00:06:42.310
we were like, let's just put
a lot of fancy stuff in it,

00:06:42.310 --> 00:06:45.990
and make it not so heavy so
you can eat other things.

00:06:45.990 --> 00:06:48.114
So that was a
long-winded explanation

00:06:48.114 --> 00:06:49.280
of what we're about to make.

00:06:49.280 --> 00:06:51.279
And then I'm just going
to demo this super-fast.

00:06:51.279 --> 00:06:54.080
So keep up, if you can.

00:06:54.080 --> 00:06:55.630
You just get a pot.

00:06:55.630 --> 00:06:57.600
My soft-cooked eggs--
the Westlake rice

00:06:57.600 --> 00:07:02.950
porridge we do always
has beef of some form.

00:07:02.950 --> 00:07:05.170
For this recipe, we
use beef cheeks, which

00:07:05.170 --> 00:07:06.900
you guys can find, I'm sure.

00:07:06.900 --> 00:07:09.329
Bi-Rite stocks them usually.

00:07:09.329 --> 00:07:11.120
If you go to your
butcher, you can get them

00:07:11.120 --> 00:07:12.670
if you ask them very
nicely for them.

00:07:12.670 --> 00:07:14.950
There's a lot of fat
and connective tissue

00:07:14.950 --> 00:07:17.870
in beef cheeks that breaks
down when you cook it

00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:19.850
very slowly, when you
braise it, and just turns

00:07:19.850 --> 00:07:22.352
into really awesome flavor.

00:07:22.352 --> 00:07:23.726
If you don't have
beef cheek, you

00:07:23.726 --> 00:07:26.490
could use-- we don't even use
beef cheek in New York anymore.

00:07:26.490 --> 00:07:29.420
We just cut up raw beef and
throw raw beef into it-- really

00:07:29.420 --> 00:07:31.680
awesome, grass-fed beef tartar.

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:38.210
And then we fold in sea urchin
and trout roe or salmon roe.

00:07:38.210 --> 00:07:39.380
But we always do an egg.

00:07:39.380 --> 00:07:40.755
I think an egg is
very important.

00:07:40.755 --> 00:07:42.740
So soft-cooking eggs
couldn't be easier.

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:46.070
I always just take an
egg, and put it into a pan

00:07:46.070 --> 00:07:47.740
without water in it.

00:07:47.740 --> 00:07:49.440
And then I cover it with water.

00:07:49.440 --> 00:07:53.814
And this is cold water.

00:07:53.814 --> 00:07:55.480
And then you just
wait for this to boil.

00:07:55.480 --> 00:07:57.921
So this should take-- I
don't know-- a while to boil.

00:07:57.921 --> 00:07:59.670
Hopefully it boils by
the time we're done.

00:07:59.670 --> 00:08:02.070
When it comes to boil,
you put a lid on it.

00:08:02.070 --> 00:08:05.110
And then you just step back
and wait 6 to 6 and 1/2

00:08:05.110 --> 00:08:07.480
minutes off the heat.

00:08:07.480 --> 00:08:08.356
Just cover it.

00:08:08.356 --> 00:08:09.230
Take it off the heat.

00:08:09.230 --> 00:08:10.460
Let it sit for 6 minutes.

00:08:10.460 --> 00:08:14.320
After 6 minutes, take it out
of the water-- preferably not

00:08:14.320 --> 00:08:15.240
with your hand.

00:08:15.240 --> 00:08:16.910
And then put it
into some ice water.

00:08:16.910 --> 00:08:17.485
Shock it.

00:08:17.485 --> 00:08:18.330
And open it up.

00:08:18.330 --> 00:08:22.060
You'll have an egg that is just
barely runny in the middle,

00:08:22.060 --> 00:08:24.219
and that white is perfectly set.

00:08:24.219 --> 00:08:25.760
A lot of mistakes
people usually make

00:08:25.760 --> 00:08:27.843
when they're soft-cooking
eggs is they drop eggs--

00:08:27.843 --> 00:08:30.170
and I do this myself--
into boiling water.

00:08:30.170 --> 00:08:34.682
What happens is the outside
of the actual egg, when

00:08:34.682 --> 00:08:37.140
it hits that hot water-- usually
the temperature of the egg

00:08:37.140 --> 00:08:39.559
itself from the
refrigerator is cold.

00:08:39.559 --> 00:08:43.100
Even if you temper it, the
temperature of that eggshell

00:08:43.100 --> 00:08:46.820
is a lot different temperature
than the boiling water.

00:08:46.820 --> 00:08:49.360
And it will actually crack
when it hits the bottom.

00:08:49.360 --> 00:08:51.210
And then you don't have
this nice round egg.

00:08:51.210 --> 00:08:54.370
You have little strands of
white egg in your water,

00:08:54.370 --> 00:08:55.230
and it doesn't work.

00:08:55.230 --> 00:08:57.250
So I think covering
it with cold water--

00:08:57.250 --> 00:09:02.970
bring it up to a boil, 6 to
7 minutes, and you're golden.

00:09:02.970 --> 00:09:05.050
Another thing that I'm
just going to hammer out

00:09:05.050 --> 00:09:08.000
really fast so we can make fun
of ourselves about this book

00:09:08.000 --> 00:09:12.530
is the rice porridge--
ratios for rice porridges

00:09:12.530 --> 00:09:14.760
can vary wildly.

00:09:14.760 --> 00:09:17.327
I like to take a
pot like this size.

00:09:17.327 --> 00:09:19.410
One of the things you want
to remember when you're

00:09:19.410 --> 00:09:22.240
making a rice porridge, if
you guys end up making this,

00:09:22.240 --> 00:09:23.770
is that rice is starch.

00:09:23.770 --> 00:09:26.641
So starch, if you don't pay
too much attention to it--

00:09:26.641 --> 00:09:28.890
how many of you guys have
been making mashed potatoes,

00:09:28.890 --> 00:09:31.900
and forgot about it,
and then just burned

00:09:31.900 --> 00:09:33.552
your mashed potatoes?

00:09:33.552 --> 00:09:35.010
No one's going to
raise their hand,

00:09:35.010 --> 00:09:38.120
but I'm sure it's happened.

00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:44.120
The ratio of rice to water
is about 12 to 16 parts water

00:09:44.120 --> 00:09:45.120
to one part rice.

00:09:45.120 --> 00:09:48.715
So literally, you need
like a gallon of water

00:09:48.715 --> 00:09:50.830
to like a cup of rice.

00:09:50.830 --> 00:09:52.580
And it makes a lot
of rice porridge.

00:09:52.580 --> 00:09:55.890
So what's great about
this dish is-- you know,

00:09:55.890 --> 00:09:57.009
Thanksgiving is coming up.

00:09:57.009 --> 00:09:59.050
If you wanted to make
something for everyone when

00:09:59.050 --> 00:10:02.105
they come over and they're all
like-- you know, you're hungry.

00:10:02.105 --> 00:10:03.780
You don't want to get too full.

00:10:03.780 --> 00:10:05.470
A nice rice broth
is really nice.

00:10:05.470 --> 00:10:06.176
It's easy.

00:10:06.176 --> 00:10:07.050
Everyone's impressed.

00:10:07.050 --> 00:10:09.295
They're like, wow,
he made congee?

00:10:09.295 --> 00:10:11.070
All you've got to do
is buy fancy stuff

00:10:11.070 --> 00:10:13.770
and put it in this rice broth.

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:15.707
And everyone will
be very impressed.

00:10:15.707 --> 00:10:18.290
CHRIS YING: You're just giving
away the entire business model.

00:10:18.290 --> 00:10:20.623
DANNY BOWIEN: This is how you
open Mission Chinese Food.

00:10:20.623 --> 00:10:22.230
Just make rice broth.

00:10:22.230 --> 00:10:24.210
Put fancy things in it.

00:10:24.210 --> 00:10:25.734
You're good.

00:10:25.734 --> 00:10:27.400
This is working out
perfectly, actually.

00:10:27.400 --> 00:10:29.200
So this water is
about to come up.

00:10:29.200 --> 00:10:30.530
It's coming up to a simmer.

00:10:30.530 --> 00:10:33.859
One of the very important things
to do-- the version of rice

00:10:33.859 --> 00:10:35.650
porridge we make, we
make it a lot thinner.

00:10:35.650 --> 00:10:39.590
So it's closer to like a
Vietnamese rice porridge

00:10:39.590 --> 00:10:42.331
than it is a Chinese
rice porridge.

00:10:42.331 --> 00:10:43.580
Neither way is right or wrong.

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:47.410
I just prefer it to
be a little thinner.

00:10:47.410 --> 00:10:50.500
Big pot, small amount of
rice-- this goes in the pot.

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:52.610
And then you toast this.

00:10:52.610 --> 00:10:56.200
You want to toast this
until it smells fragrant.

00:10:56.200 --> 00:10:58.106
I always use jasmine rice.

00:10:58.106 --> 00:10:59.230
I really love jasmine rice.

00:10:59.230 --> 00:11:00.862
I think the flavor's amazing.

00:11:00.862 --> 00:11:02.070
You can use short-grain rice.

00:11:02.070 --> 00:11:03.820
But know that if you
use short-grain rice,

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:06.540
it's going to get a lot thicker.

00:11:06.540 --> 00:11:07.040
Yeah.

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:08.220
So that's it.

