Toast this on this
thing-- on a stove,

00:11:11.810 --> 00:11:15.720
or whatever you have
at home, a hot plate--

00:11:15.720 --> 00:11:16.710
until it's fragrant.

00:11:16.710 --> 00:11:18.876
You don't want it to be
brown or anything like that.

00:11:18.876 --> 00:11:20.890
And then you want to
add your water or stock.

00:11:20.890 --> 00:11:24.450
I always add water.

00:11:24.450 --> 00:11:28.090
And then it's kind of
crazy, because the way

00:11:28.090 --> 00:11:32.557
I was taught to do this,
the lady at Duc Loi--

00:11:32.557 --> 00:11:34.390
does anyone know what
that grocery store is?

00:11:34.390 --> 00:11:37.726
There's a market in the
Mission, next to Mission Chinese

00:11:37.726 --> 00:11:38.600
Food, called Duc Loi.

00:11:38.600 --> 00:11:39.920
It's a Vietnamese market.

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:41.080
The owner's name is Amanda.

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:43.490
And she was just like, oh,
when I make my rice porridge,

00:11:43.490 --> 00:11:45.110
I just put a whole
chicken in there.

00:11:45.110 --> 00:11:47.460
And I was like, OK.

00:11:47.460 --> 00:11:48.440
But it really works.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:51.949
Because all the
flavor in chicken

00:11:51.949 --> 00:11:52.990
is really in the protein.

00:11:52.990 --> 00:11:55.240
And there's flavor you
can pull out of the bones

00:11:55.240 --> 00:11:56.670
if you're making
a chicken stock.

00:11:56.670 --> 00:11:59.045
But if you just drop a whole
chicken into simmering water

00:11:59.045 --> 00:12:03.819
with rice, the chicken
actually becomes very tender

00:12:03.819 --> 00:12:05.360
because it's cooking
in a rice broth.

00:12:05.360 --> 00:12:07.070
There's something about the
rice that helps break down

00:12:07.070 --> 00:12:08.210
the protein gently.

00:12:08.210 --> 00:12:09.580
And it makes it really tender.

00:12:09.580 --> 00:12:11.755
And then you get all the
wonderful flavor of chicken

00:12:11.755 --> 00:12:13.130
that goes into
the rice porridge.

00:12:13.130 --> 00:12:15.590
So a long story
short-- you're not

00:12:15.590 --> 00:12:17.730
making a chicken
stock for four hours

00:12:17.730 --> 00:12:20.370
and then straining it and
then pouring it into here.

00:12:20.370 --> 00:12:21.320
Just take a chicken.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:22.290
Put some salt on it.

00:12:22.290 --> 00:12:25.010
Leave it overnight
in your refrigerator.

00:12:25.010 --> 00:12:28.160
If you're not making a lot, just
take a couple legs of chicken.

00:12:28.160 --> 00:12:29.754
If you're making a big pot
like this, you can do it.

00:12:29.754 --> 00:12:30.920
Put a whole chicken in here.

00:12:30.920 --> 00:12:34.290
And then just drop it in there.

00:12:34.290 --> 00:12:35.300
Cover it.

00:12:35.300 --> 00:12:36.620
Bring it up to a simmer.

00:12:36.620 --> 00:12:39.230
And then let it simmer
for about-- until it

00:12:39.230 --> 00:12:40.010
starts to thicken.

00:12:40.010 --> 00:12:41.650
Stir it a lot.

00:12:41.650 --> 00:12:43.950
Don't let it stick
to the bottom.

00:12:43.950 --> 00:12:46.677
This is boiling now, so
I'm going to take it off.

00:12:46.677 --> 00:12:48.260
And then we'll just
put a lid on that.

00:12:48.260 --> 00:12:50.610
And then I'm going to act
like I'm toasting this.

00:12:50.610 --> 00:12:52.234
Chris, do you have
any questions for me

00:12:52.234 --> 00:12:54.150
at all while I'm
toasting this rice?

00:12:54.150 --> 00:12:56.219
CHRIS YING: Huh.

00:12:56.219 --> 00:12:59.630
Uh-- no.

00:12:59.630 --> 00:13:01.630
DANNY BOWIEN: I have not
seen "The Martian" yet.

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:05.570
So I don't know.

00:13:05.570 --> 00:13:07.210
Yes, I like Taylor
Swift's new album.

00:13:07.210 --> 00:13:09.216
I don't know what
else you-- so anyways.

00:13:09.216 --> 00:13:09.840
Toast the rice.

00:13:09.840 --> 00:13:11.580
This is rice that's toasted.

00:13:11.580 --> 00:13:14.090
We would have added
like 12 to 16--

00:13:14.090 --> 00:13:16.336
I would start out with
like 12 parts water.

00:13:16.336 --> 00:13:18.710
And then what will happen is
if it starts to get thicker,

00:13:18.710 --> 00:13:20.450
you add more water.

00:13:20.450 --> 00:13:21.010
Adjust it.

00:13:21.010 --> 00:13:23.551
You're just going to season at
the very end with a little bit

00:13:23.551 --> 00:13:26.150
of fish sauce and salt.
And the ratios for all that

00:13:26.150 --> 00:13:26.959
are in the book.

00:13:26.959 --> 00:13:28.500
That's why I'm not
going to tell you.

00:13:28.500 --> 00:13:30.442
So you all buy the
book afterwards.

00:13:30.442 --> 00:13:32.650
CHRIS YING: It will look
kind of ridiculous at first.

00:13:32.650 --> 00:13:34.305
You'll be like, this
is way too much water.

00:13:34.305 --> 00:13:34.452
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:13:34.452 --> 00:13:34.600
It'll look like--

00:13:34.600 --> 00:13:37.016
CHRIS YING: There's no way
this is going to come together.

00:13:37.016 --> 00:13:39.240
DANNY BOWIEN: But
it will thicken.

00:13:39.240 --> 00:13:41.159
It'll be where you
want it to be, ideally.

00:13:41.159 --> 00:13:42.700
And if it's not,
you can just adjust.

00:13:45.120 --> 00:13:45.620
That's it.

00:13:45.620 --> 00:13:46.320
CHRIS YING: Do you
have a real portion?

00:13:46.320 --> 00:13:46.590
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:13:46.590 --> 00:13:49.006
And I guess I can just take a
real portion of the-- do you

00:13:49.006 --> 00:13:50.512
guys have the real bowl of--

00:13:50.512 --> 00:13:52.136
CHRIS YING: Can we
just get a bowl of--

00:13:54.444 --> 00:13:56.110
DANNY BOWIEN: So
really quickly, there's

00:13:56.110 --> 00:13:57.526
a recipe for beef
cheeks in there.

00:13:57.526 --> 00:13:58.760
The beef cheeks are braised.

00:13:58.760 --> 00:14:00.970
So after we braise
them, we always

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:02.835
let-- if you braise
something, that

00:14:02.835 --> 00:14:05.054
means you're just cooking
it in a flavorful liquid.

00:14:05.054 --> 00:14:06.970
You always want to let
that cool in the liquid

00:14:06.970 --> 00:14:07.803
that it's cooked in.

00:14:07.803 --> 00:14:10.560
You don't want to take it out
after you-- it's very tempting.

00:14:10.560 --> 00:14:11.640
You pull something
out of the oven.

00:14:11.640 --> 00:14:12.940
You're braising a
whole piece of meat.

00:14:12.940 --> 00:14:13.900
You're like, oh,
I think it's done.

00:14:13.900 --> 00:14:14.704
It's jiggly.

00:14:14.704 --> 00:14:15.370
You take it out.

00:14:15.370 --> 00:14:16.260
It just dries out.

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:18.230
You want to let it cool in
the liquid it's cooked in.

00:14:18.230 --> 00:14:19.146
CHRIS YING: Thank you.

00:14:19.146 --> 00:14:22.570
DANNY BOWIEN: So it stays
really juicy and delicious.

00:14:22.570 --> 00:14:26.640
What happens next, after
it cools, is the stock

00:14:26.640 --> 00:14:29.020
becomes this gel, because
of all the connective--

00:14:29.020 --> 00:14:31.240
all of the collagen
in the beef cheeks.

00:14:31.240 --> 00:14:32.420
Save this stuff.

00:14:32.420 --> 00:14:35.084
This stuff is like liquid gold.

00:14:35.084 --> 00:14:36.750
We like to add this
back to the porridge

00:14:36.750 --> 00:14:38.980
so you have a little
bit more beef flavor.

00:14:38.980 --> 00:14:40.490
I'm going to stop talking
about the rice porridge now.

00:14:40.490 --> 00:14:41.730
Let's talk about
the book, Chris.

00:14:41.730 --> 00:14:42.170
Because that's--

00:14:42.170 --> 00:14:42.266
CHRIS YING: Yes.

00:14:42.266 --> 00:14:43.420
Let's talk about the book.

00:14:43.420 --> 00:14:45.336
I mean, an interesting
thing with beef cheeks,

00:14:45.336 --> 00:14:48.620
though, is the reason why Danny
and Mission Chinese started

00:14:48.620 --> 00:14:49.630
using beef cheeks--

00:14:49.630 --> 00:14:50.080
DANNY BOWIEN: They're cheap.

00:14:50.080 --> 00:14:51.110
CHRIS YING: Because
they're cheap.

00:14:51.110 --> 00:14:53.850
There's these inefficiencies,
sort of-- I mean, you guys all

00:14:53.850 --> 00:14:56.317
know about the nose-to-tail
cooking and using

00:14:56.317 --> 00:14:57.900
the whole animal and
things like that.

00:14:57.900 --> 00:15:01.050
Those are realities of having
a restaurant, actually.

00:15:01.050 --> 00:15:01.812
Danny comes in.

00:15:01.812 --> 00:15:03.020
He looks at a list of prices.

00:15:03.020 --> 00:15:04.200
And he's like, oh.

00:15:04.200 --> 00:15:06.040
Beef cheeks are like $4 a pound.

00:15:06.040 --> 00:15:07.670
Let's do something
with beef cheeks.

00:15:07.670 --> 00:15:11.037
And that's really the spirit
of what Mission Chinese

00:15:11.037 --> 00:15:11.870
Food was originally.

00:15:11.870 --> 00:15:13.828
It was like, let's do
the best with what we can

00:15:13.828 --> 00:15:16.250
and find out cool
ways to use things.

00:15:16.250 --> 00:15:17.860
Since then, beef
cheeks are probably

00:15:17.860 --> 00:15:19.030
quadrupled in price now.

00:15:19.030 --> 00:15:19.102
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:15:19.102 --> 00:15:20.018
It's really expensive.

00:15:20.018 --> 00:15:21.890
That's why we just
use raw beef now.

00:15:21.890 --> 00:15:23.870
Because that's
the-- you don't have

00:15:23.870 --> 00:15:26.410
to pay someone to braise it.

00:15:26.410 --> 00:15:28.250
It just became a
matter of economics.

00:15:28.250 --> 00:15:29.170
But it's funny.

00:15:29.170 --> 00:15:32.810
Like lobsters-- they used
to just throw them away.

00:15:32.810 --> 00:15:34.330
Or they'd send
them to prisoners.

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:35.788
I don't know if
you guys knew that.

00:15:35.788 --> 00:15:38.140
But lobster used to be this
thing that was frowned upon.

00:15:38.140 --> 00:15:41.350
And they would--
literally, I think,

00:15:41.350 --> 00:15:43.620
you got lobster
to eat in prison.

00:15:43.620 --> 00:15:45.760
That was your food.

00:15:45.760 --> 00:15:47.020
Anyway, this is really boring.

00:15:47.020 --> 00:15:49.692
Let's talk about
the book some more.

00:15:49.692 --> 00:15:50.400
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:15:50.400 --> 00:15:52.316
I mean, we were sort of
hinting at it earlier.

00:15:52.316 --> 00:15:56.730
This book is-- like Danny
said, we sold this book

00:15:56.730 --> 00:16:00.570
to our publisher before
Mission Chinese had really

00:16:00.570 --> 00:16:04.150
proven itself to be a
national restaurant that

00:16:04.150 --> 00:16:05.740
deserved to have a cookbook.

00:16:05.740 --> 00:16:09.590
And so the publisher took
a crazy gamble on us.

00:16:09.590 --> 00:16:12.450
And the interesting
thing for me,

00:16:12.450 --> 00:16:16.620
as the person writing this
book with Danny, was none of it

00:16:16.620 --> 00:16:18.120
was reflective.

00:16:18.120 --> 00:16:19.740
We were writing
it as these things

00:16:19.740 --> 00:16:21.280
were happening, as
crazy things were

00:16:21.280 --> 00:16:22.530
happening, at Mission Chinese.

00:16:22.530 --> 00:16:25.130
I think there was one incident
where Danny and I were hanging

00:16:25.130 --> 00:16:26.255
out talking about the book.

00:16:26.255 --> 00:16:27.950
And he was like,
I'm really proud,

00:16:27.950 --> 00:16:31.910
and we should really talk
about in the book, that nobody

00:16:31.910 --> 00:16:34.310
has ever quit or been
fired from this restaurant

00:16:34.310 --> 00:16:37.305
because we're just
this happy family.

00:16:37.305 --> 00:16:38.430
And then the next morning--

00:16:38.430 --> 00:16:39.420
DANNY BOWIEN: In
San Francisco only.

00:16:39.420 --> 00:16:39.822
CHRIS YING: In San Francisco.

00:16:39.822 --> 00:16:40.626
DANNY BOWIEN: Not
the one in New York.

00:16:40.626 --> 00:16:42.350
We've had like 190 employees.

00:16:42.350 --> 00:16:44.058
CHRIS YING: And then
the next morning, he

00:16:44.058 --> 00:16:46.015
was like-- we were
staying in a geodesic dome

00:16:46.015 --> 00:16:48.140
in the Russian River because
we were hunkering down

00:16:48.140 --> 00:16:48.770
to work on this book.

00:16:48.770 --> 00:16:51.050
And then the next day, he got
a text that was like, Dan,

00:16:51.050 --> 00:16:52.060
you've got to come
back to the restaurant.

00:16:52.060 --> 00:16:54.570
One of the cooks just punched
the other one in the face.

00:16:54.570 --> 00:16:55.560
We've got to deal
with this thing.

00:16:55.560 --> 00:16:57.420
DANNY BOWIEN: That's
just like-- that's that.

00:16:57.420 --> 00:16:59.670
CHRIS YING: That's just how
the book was put together.

00:16:59.670 --> 00:17:02.265
It was like every time we
thought we had our story down--

00:17:02.265 --> 00:17:05.210
DANNY BOWIEN: We got punched in
the face by an angry line cook.

00:17:05.210 --> 00:17:08.310
CHRIS YING: We got punched in
the face by an angry line cook.

00:17:11.880 --> 00:17:15.480
The recipes are true to what
happened at the restaurant.

00:17:15.480 --> 00:17:18.290
Like Liv was kind
of hinting, when

00:17:18.290 --> 00:17:20.630
Danny was opening the
New York restaurant,

00:17:20.630 --> 00:17:21.778
the computer crashed.

00:17:21.778 --> 00:17:23.319
And he called me
and was like, do you

00:17:23.319 --> 00:17:24.619
have our recipes
backed up somewhere?

00:17:24.619 --> 00:17:25.160
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:17:25.160 --> 00:17:25.660
Oh, my god.

00:17:25.660 --> 00:17:26.640
It was crazy.

00:17:26.640 --> 00:17:27.540
It was insane.

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:30.050
We lost everything.

00:17:30.050 --> 00:17:32.492
And he, actually--
because of Chris,

00:17:32.492 --> 00:17:33.950
there's still
Mission Chinese food.

00:17:33.950 --> 00:17:35.760
Because we didn't have
them written down.

00:17:35.760 --> 00:17:36.560
I didn't have them written down.

00:17:36.560 --> 00:17:36.780
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:17:36.780 --> 00:17:37.400
DANNY BOWIEN: But we do now.

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:38.990
And now we're very organized.

00:17:38.990 --> 00:17:42.080
It took a long
time to get there.

00:17:42.080 --> 00:17:42.580
But yeah.

00:17:42.580 --> 00:17:43.770
I mean, I don't know.

00:17:43.770 --> 00:17:45.410
We're super-proud of this thing.

00:17:45.410 --> 00:17:48.111
It's like nothing-- I
think it says in the book.

00:17:48.111 --> 00:17:50.610
It's not like we're at the top
of the mountain looking back,

00:17:50.610 --> 00:17:53.240
and this is just a reflection
of what we've accomplished.

00:17:53.240 --> 00:17:56.062
It's literally us just trying to
get our shit together, like ah,

00:17:56.062 --> 00:17:57.020
everything's happening.

00:17:57.020 --> 00:17:59.420
And all this positive
stuff happens.

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:01.730
All this really
negative stuff happens.

00:18:01.730 --> 00:18:05.510
And it's just all there.

00:18:05.510 --> 00:18:08.500
It's just like,
well, OK, let's--

00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:10.732
I can't even-- we would get
in these yelling matches

00:18:10.732 --> 00:18:12.940
with each other, because
there was never enough time.

00:18:12.940 --> 00:18:14.606
How are we going to
get this thing done?

00:18:14.606 --> 00:18:17.441
How are we going to
get this book done?

00:18:17.441 --> 00:18:17.940
It's funny.

00:18:17.940 --> 00:18:20.150
Because when it was actually
finished, we were like, oh wow.

00:18:20.150 --> 00:18:21.180
This is really amazing.

00:18:21.180 --> 00:18:23.374
I thought we didn't have enough.

00:18:23.374 --> 00:18:24.790
You never think
you can do enough.

00:18:24.790 --> 00:18:25.840
You're like, oh, man.

00:18:25.840 --> 00:18:29.327
It needs more of this
and this and this.

00:18:29.327 --> 00:18:30.410
And it has a lot of stuff.

00:18:30.410 --> 00:18:32.960
It's a lot of content.

00:18:32.960 --> 00:18:34.200
LIV WU: I have a question.

00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:35.620
DANNY BOWIEN: Go.

00:18:35.620 --> 00:18:42.460
LIV WU: So division of labor--
you did the recording, Chris?

00:18:42.460 --> 00:18:43.440
You did the talking?

00:18:43.440 --> 00:18:44.220
You said, one cup of rice.

00:18:44.220 --> 00:18:44.505
DANNY BOWIEN: I talk.

00:18:44.505 --> 00:18:46.420
I'm really good at
just talking at people.

00:18:46.420 --> 00:18:48.520
Like you can see,
I'm just rambling on

00:18:48.520 --> 00:18:49.590
and going in circles.

00:18:49.590 --> 00:18:51.510
So I just would talk to Chris.

00:18:51.510 --> 00:18:53.746
And he would just
painstakingly listen to me.

00:18:53.746 --> 00:18:55.370
Sometimes I think
you were just playing

00:18:55.370 --> 00:18:57.232
Xbox and just recording.

00:18:57.232 --> 00:18:58.690
Because, I mean,
I was in New York.

00:18:58.690 --> 00:18:59.452
And you were here.

00:18:59.452 --> 00:19:00.160
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:19:00.160 --> 00:19:05.180
It's an odd process,
honestly, to be writing

00:19:05.180 --> 00:19:07.810
a story like this one, or
to be recording recipes

00:19:07.810 --> 00:19:10.554
of a restaurant
that's still evolving.

00:19:10.554 --> 00:19:12.970
And that's why Danny's saying
we kept on adding and adding

00:19:12.970 --> 00:19:14.178
and adding and couldn't stop.

00:19:14.178 --> 00:19:17.960
It's because-- for example,
the recipe for Mapo tofu that's

00:19:17.960 --> 00:19:21.120
in this book is probably
the 35th version

00:19:21.120 --> 00:19:23.770
of that recipe that's been
served at the restaurant.

00:19:23.770 --> 00:19:28.227
And that's exciting to me
as a diner and as a writer,

00:19:28.227 --> 00:19:30.560
for somebody who wants to
keep on refining and improving

00:19:30.560 --> 00:19:31.470
their product.

00:19:31.470 --> 00:19:33.900
It's like nerve-wracking
for a chef

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:35.879
to put out a version
that they're like,

00:19:35.879 --> 00:19:37.420
this is going to be
better next week.

00:19:37.420 --> 00:19:38.456
And everyone who's
going to have the book

00:19:38.456 --> 00:19:40.330
is going to have a
slightly shittier version.

00:19:40.330 --> 00:19:42.440
DANNY BOWIEN: No, but
it's good, though.

00:19:42.440 --> 00:19:44.090
It's funny.

00:19:44.090 --> 00:19:45.820
The way Mission
Chinese started is

00:19:45.820 --> 00:19:48.610
we had no formal-- I've never
cooked in a Chinese restaurant.

00:19:48.610 --> 00:19:49.460
I'm not Chinese.

00:19:49.460 --> 00:19:52.930
I actually grew up in
Oklahoma until I was like 19.

00:19:52.930 --> 00:19:55.060
And then I moved
to San Francisco

00:19:55.060 --> 00:19:59.900
and spent like 10 years here,
and then moved to New York.

00:19:59.900 --> 00:20:02.380
So yeah, I'm not a Chinese chef.

00:20:02.380 --> 00:20:03.830
It's pretty insane.

00:20:03.830 --> 00:20:08.260
So then because of that, trying
to learn all these recipes,

00:20:08.260 --> 00:20:11.890
we would come out the gates
swinging for the fences.

00:20:11.890 --> 00:20:14.940
It was like, how can we make
Mapo tofu 300 times better

00:20:14.940 --> 00:20:15.940
than it actually is?

00:20:15.940 --> 00:20:17.590
And how many
ingredients can we use?

00:20:17.590 --> 00:20:19.275
And so the first
version of Mapo tofu

00:20:19.275 --> 00:20:21.840
had like 33 aromatic
ingredients in it.

00:20:21.840 --> 00:20:24.780
And then we got that
out of our systems.

00:20:24.780 --> 00:20:27.185
And then we realized,
well, it's kind

00:20:27.185 --> 00:20:29.610
of like linguine and clams.

00:20:29.610 --> 00:20:32.450
You can't really do much to
improve linguine and clams,

00:20:32.450 --> 00:20:34.514
in its truest form.

00:20:34.514 --> 00:20:35.680
You're not going to do much.

00:20:35.680 --> 00:20:36.810
It's just a perfect flavor.

00:20:36.810 --> 00:20:38.170
It's like a caprese salad.

00:20:38.170 --> 00:20:39.300
There's tomatoes.

00:20:39.300 --> 00:20:41.760
There's insanely good
buffalo mozzarella, and basil

00:20:41.760 --> 00:20:43.920
and olive oil and sea salt.

00:20:43.920 --> 00:20:47.250
You can't-- you can do a lot
of things to dress that up.

00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:49.650
But we're acknowledging
the fact that yeah,

00:20:49.650 --> 00:20:52.690
maybe sometimes you need
to pull back on the 33.

00:20:52.690 --> 00:20:54.530
So now there's
eight ingredients.

00:20:54.530 --> 00:20:56.580
And we're just making
regular Mapo tofu.

00:20:56.580 --> 00:21:00.380
But we're using a little bit of
aged beef fat and some really

00:21:00.380 --> 00:21:01.885
amazing pork.

00:21:01.885 --> 00:21:04.910
We're just elevating the
ingredients that we use,

00:21:04.910 --> 00:21:08.480
and then learning the
technique, and applying it.

00:21:08.480 --> 00:21:09.890
So it's really interesting.

00:21:09.890 --> 00:21:12.630
Again, there's no-- I think
the book really spells out

00:21:12.630 --> 00:21:15.610
how to make Chinese food-- or
our version of Chinese food--

00:21:15.610 --> 00:21:16.610
if you feel like it.

00:21:16.610 --> 00:21:19.510
And it also is
very entertaining.

00:21:19.510 --> 00:21:22.350
Because you can actually see
how it all has been evolving

00:21:22.350 --> 00:21:24.280
and has evolved
into what it is now.

00:21:24.280 --> 00:21:27.930
LIV WU: So it's interesting to
me that your process was never,

00:21:27.930 --> 00:21:28.870
let's go to China.

00:21:28.870 --> 00:21:29.870
Let's go to [INAUDIBLE].

00:21:29.870 --> 00:21:31.036
CHRIS YING: Oh, we did that.

00:21:31.036 --> 00:21:32.650
DANNY BOWIEN: We did that.

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:35.010
CHRIS YING: We did that three
months-- this is actually

00:21:35.010 --> 00:21:36.560
the craziest story.

00:21:36.560 --> 00:21:37.530
LIV WU: Let's hear it.

00:21:37.530 --> 00:21:38.610
CHRIS YING: I somehow
talked Danny into,

00:21:38.610 --> 00:21:41.260
like, we should do this
cookbook, when the restaurant

00:21:41.260 --> 00:21:43.932
was like a week old.

00:21:43.932 --> 00:21:45.890
I was like, you know what
would be really great

00:21:45.890 --> 00:21:48.200
for this cookbook is
if we flew to China

00:21:48.200 --> 00:21:52.340
and you did a pop-up in
China and saw how that went.

00:21:52.340 --> 00:21:54.100
DANNY BOWIEN: So I'd
been working inside

00:21:54.100 --> 00:21:56.709
of Mission Chinese Food
for a little while.

00:21:56.709 --> 00:21:58.750
But Mission Chinese Food
was originally a pop-up.

00:22:02.720 --> 00:22:04.820
Mission Chinese Food
in San Francisco

00:22:04.820 --> 00:22:06.420
is owned by a Chinese family.

00:22:06.420 --> 00:22:07.762
It's called Lung Shan.

00:22:07.762 --> 00:22:09.220
The restaurant is
called Lung Shan.

00:22:09.220 --> 00:22:10.920
There's no actual
Mission Chinese Food

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:12.776
that exists in San Francisco.

00:22:12.776 --> 00:22:14.150
It was actually
called Lung Shan.

00:22:14.150 --> 00:22:16.441
And we did a pop-up inside
called Mission Chinese Food.

00:22:16.441 --> 00:22:17.600
And it just never ended.

00:22:17.600 --> 00:22:21.460
So there's no-- I mean,
it's just Lung Shan.

00:22:21.460 --> 00:22:24.200
But what happens is, I'm sitting
there in this restaurant.

00:22:24.200 --> 00:22:25.400
I don't speak Chinese.

00:22:25.400 --> 00:22:27.440
I was working with
only Chinese cooks,

00:22:27.440 --> 00:22:29.850
showing them my
version of Chinese food

00:22:29.850 --> 00:22:31.109
and how to make Chinese food.

00:22:31.109 --> 00:22:32.650
They're looking at
me like I'm crazy.

00:22:32.650 --> 00:22:33.850
And then we go to China.

00:22:33.850 --> 00:22:35.100
So I have this weird
chip on my shoulder.

00:22:35.100 --> 00:22:36.540
I'm like, well, if I'm
doing everything wrong,

00:22:36.540 --> 00:22:38.498
I'm going to see how
everyone's doing it right.

00:22:38.498 --> 00:22:41.170
So the first trip to
China-- we've taken two--

00:22:41.170 --> 00:22:42.490
was kind of an ill-fated trip.

00:22:42.490 --> 00:22:47.300
And it was just me kind of being
a young, ignorant, immature

00:22:47.300 --> 00:22:49.370
cook, and being like,
prove to me that this

00:22:49.370 --> 00:22:50.720
is better than what I do.

00:22:50.720 --> 00:22:54.240
And then the second trip was
actually the most telling.

00:22:54.240 --> 00:22:56.500
Because at that
point, I'd kind of

00:22:56.500 --> 00:23:01.350
realized that I was very
far from being the best

00:23:01.350 --> 00:23:03.650
chef in the world, or
knowing anything about what

00:23:03.650 --> 00:23:06.140
I know how to do now.

00:23:06.140 --> 00:23:08.290
And that was just
a good life lesson.

00:23:08.290 --> 00:23:12.904
It was like, don't be a
little punk, immature kid,

00:23:12.904 --> 00:23:14.320
and you can learn
a lot of things.

00:23:14.320 --> 00:23:14.820
So yeah.

00:23:14.820 --> 00:23:16.340
We've been to China twice.

00:23:16.340 --> 00:23:17.920
The first trip
was right before--

00:23:17.920 --> 00:23:20.003
CHRIS YING: The first trip
was specifically funny.

00:23:20.003 --> 00:23:23.370
Because one of the
big newspaper articles

00:23:23.370 --> 00:23:27.360
that made Mission Chinese San
Francisco a big deal was Mark

00:23:27.360 --> 00:23:29.360
Bittman wrote an article
in "The New York Times"

00:23:29.360 --> 00:23:31.230
about Mission
Chinese and it being

00:23:31.230 --> 00:23:32.660
this cutting-edge restaurant.

00:23:32.660 --> 00:23:36.437
And when something like that
happens to your restaurant--

00:23:36.437 --> 00:23:38.520
when "The New York Times"
declares your restaurant

00:23:38.520 --> 00:23:40.900
to be one of the most
important ones in the country--

00:23:40.900 --> 00:23:42.770
you are besieged with business.

00:23:42.770 --> 00:23:46.070
I think that the
day that article

00:23:46.070 --> 00:23:48.802
was scheduled to come out, Danny
was like, let's go to China.

00:23:48.802 --> 00:23:49.760
Let's just not be open.

00:23:49.760 --> 00:23:51.930
Let's just close the
restaurant and go.

00:23:51.930 --> 00:23:52.540
DANNY BOWIEN: Well,
we couldn't handle it.

00:23:52.540 --> 00:23:53.640
CHRIS YING: I don't want
to deal with any of it.

00:23:53.640 --> 00:23:53.766
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:23:53.766 --> 00:23:55.250
So we're getting pretty busy.

00:23:55.250 --> 00:23:57.150
And we're orchestrating
this thing.

00:23:57.150 --> 00:23:59.040
Because Lung Shan was
still doing Lung Shan's

00:23:59.040 --> 00:24:01.510
150-item Chinese takeout menu.

00:24:01.510 --> 00:24:03.860
And we were doing Mission
Chinese Food next to them.

00:24:03.860 --> 00:24:05.810
So their wok burner was here.

00:24:05.810 --> 00:24:06.560
And ours was here.

00:24:06.560 --> 00:24:08.870
And we were just
getting hammered.

00:24:08.870 --> 00:24:11.920
And I was like, there's
no way that we're

00:24:11.920 --> 00:24:16.152
going to be able to handle
this onslaught of people

00:24:16.152 --> 00:24:17.110
that are going to come.

00:24:17.110 --> 00:24:19.370
So let's just close and
go to China for a week.

00:24:19.370 --> 00:24:21.460
And then we'll hopefully
bond with each other--

00:24:21.460 --> 00:24:24.699
because we went
with the owners--

00:24:24.699 --> 00:24:26.740
and kind of get our shit
together so that when we

00:24:26.740 --> 00:24:29.800
come back, we can all survive.

00:24:29.800 --> 00:24:30.910
It was a great trip.

00:24:30.910 --> 00:24:34.269
It was a good trip
in a lot of ways.

00:24:34.269 --> 00:24:35.310
I was very uncomfortable.

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:37.030
I was probably whining
a lot about stuff.

00:24:37.030 --> 00:24:37.970
But it was great.

00:24:37.970 --> 00:24:41.120
Because we came back and then
it got really crazy busy.

00:24:41.120 --> 00:24:43.350
I mean, the first year
of Mission Chinese--

00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:46.940
I remember Michael Bauer came
into the Mission Chinese Food.

00:24:46.940 --> 00:24:48.740
You guys should know
who Michael Bauer is.

00:24:48.740 --> 00:24:50.537
He's the San
Francisco food critic.

00:24:50.537 --> 00:24:52.120
And you know, there's
a song and dance

00:24:52.120 --> 00:24:53.490
that you do in the
restaurants where

00:24:53.490 --> 00:24:54.860
you act like you don't
know who the food critic is

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:56.160
when they come in.

00:24:56.160 --> 00:25:01.350
And then they act like
they're anonymous.

00:25:01.350 --> 00:25:05.000
But obviously, as a chef, you're
like, holy shit everybody.

00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:06.030
The food critic is here.

00:25:06.030 --> 00:25:07.738
Make sure the tables
around them are VIP.

00:25:07.738 --> 00:25:09.680
Make sure that table's VIP.

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:12.190
Just let me taste everything
before it goes out.

00:25:12.190 --> 00:25:15.120
But at Mission Chinese
Food, we were just

00:25:15.120 --> 00:25:16.120
kind of screwing around.

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:17.130
It was our thing.

00:25:17.130 --> 00:25:22.210
It was like our little
boys club, I guess.

00:25:22.210 --> 00:25:24.544
We were just playing around
trying to make Chinese food.

00:25:24.544 --> 00:25:25.459
I remember he came in.

00:25:25.459 --> 00:25:27.720
And I walked next door to
Commonwealth that had just

00:25:27.720 --> 00:25:29.120
opened-- it hadn't opened yet.

00:25:29.120 --> 00:25:30.560
And I was talking to Jason Fox.

00:25:30.560 --> 00:25:31.500
I was like, hey, how's it going?

00:25:31.500 --> 00:25:31.920
He was like, good.

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:32.400
I was like, oh yeah.

00:25:32.400 --> 00:25:33.675
Michael Bauer's
next door right now.

00:25:33.675 --> 00:25:34.730
He's just having lunch.

00:25:34.730 --> 00:25:36.140
He's like, oh, that's because
you're getting a review.

00:25:36.140 --> 00:25:38.299
You should probably go
back over there right now.

00:25:38.299 --> 00:25:39.090
I was like, oh, no.

00:25:39.090 --> 00:25:41.660
There's no-- why would--
there's no way in hell.

00:25:41.660 --> 00:25:43.480
And so I had no idea.

00:25:43.480 --> 00:25:44.920
I was like, there's no way.

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:46.510
CHRIS YING: You thought that
Bauer was just stopping in.

00:25:46.510 --> 00:25:48.190
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah, he
was having a casual lunch.

00:25:48.190 --> 00:25:48.590
CHRIS YING: The idea that
Mission Chinese would

00:25:48.590 --> 00:25:50.574
be reviewed was so
preposterous that he just

00:25:50.574 --> 00:25:52.990
assumed that he was hanging
out having lunch or something.

00:25:52.990 --> 00:25:54.020
DANNY BOWIEN: I
thought the second time

00:25:54.020 --> 00:25:56.450
he came in, I was going up
to him like, hey, Michael.

00:25:56.450 --> 00:25:57.559
What's going on?

00:25:57.559 --> 00:25:59.350
Because I'd seen him
at so many restaurants

00:25:59.350 --> 00:26:00.225
I'd worked at before.

00:26:00.225 --> 00:26:01.530
You know who that is.

00:26:01.530 --> 00:26:08.880
And then the article that
really-- the most proud I've

00:26:08.880 --> 00:26:10.975
been is whenever
Michael Bauer named--

00:26:10.975 --> 00:26:12.516
that's when things
really popped off,

00:26:12.516 --> 00:26:16.650
is when Michael Bauer
named me as a rising star

00:26:16.650 --> 00:26:19.325
chef in like 2011 or 2012.

00:26:19.325 --> 00:26:21.200
And that was when it
was just, like, oh, god.

00:26:21.200 --> 00:26:22.480
This is becoming serious.

00:26:22.480 --> 00:26:24.800
All while working in this
restaurant that's not mine,

00:26:24.800 --> 00:26:26.751
and with owners
that had no idea.

00:26:26.751 --> 00:26:28.750
They were like, why do
you make things so spicy?

00:26:32.690 --> 00:26:35.060
CHRIS YING: So the whole
Mission Chinese Food story

00:26:35.060 --> 00:26:38.754
is success in
spite of ourselves.

00:26:38.754 --> 00:26:40.920
Closing down the day that
Bittman's article came out

00:26:40.920 --> 00:26:44.140
is like a Christmas tree
lot closing for December.

00:26:44.140 --> 00:26:45.619
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:26:45.619 --> 00:26:46.660
CHRIS YING: It was crazy.

00:26:46.660 --> 00:26:47.159
But hey.

00:26:47.159 --> 00:26:49.070
We have to get to
another thing here.

00:26:49.070 --> 00:26:49.942
DANNY BOWIEN: Oh, is it
time for that already?

00:26:49.942 --> 00:26:52.317
CHRIS YING: So ostensibly we
made this porridge because--

00:26:52.317 --> 00:26:53.733
DANNY BOWIEN: We
like to just be--

00:26:53.733 --> 00:26:55.860
CHRIS YING: Here, plate
this thing while we finish.

00:26:55.860 --> 00:26:56.760
DANNY BOWIEN: Oh,
this is the porridge.

00:26:56.760 --> 00:26:57.620
CHRIS YING: Yeah,
this is the porridge.

00:26:57.620 --> 00:26:58.480
DANNY BOWIEN: Oh, OK.

00:26:58.480 --> 00:27:00.521
CHRIS YING: So Thanksgiving
is around the corner.

00:27:00.521 --> 00:27:03.751
And every single year for
Thanksgiving at my house,

00:27:03.751 --> 00:27:06.000
once the turkey's sort of
picked clean and everything,

00:27:06.000 --> 00:27:08.520
we make stock out of the bones.

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:12.820
We just simmer the hell out of
it forever and ever and ever,

00:27:12.820 --> 00:27:15.410
and then make rice
porridge out of it.

00:27:15.410 --> 00:27:18.010
So ostensibly this
is a themed thing.

00:27:18.010 --> 00:27:20.170
And when we were getting
ready to come out here,

00:27:20.170 --> 00:27:22.890
we were talking to Victoria and
talking to some of the Googlers

00:27:22.890 --> 00:27:24.390
about what would
be a fun thing that

00:27:24.390 --> 00:27:26.190
would help make
this talk go faster

00:27:26.190 --> 00:27:28.660
and give Danny and I
less responsibility.

00:27:28.660 --> 00:27:31.870
And the idea was that we
would get one of you guys

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:36.950
to show us a dish that was sort
of Mission Chinese-inspired

00:27:36.950 --> 00:27:39.350
for Thanksgiving.

00:27:39.350 --> 00:27:43.230
And so a few of you
guys sent in recipes.

00:27:43.230 --> 00:27:46.340
And I picked one
because it seemed

00:27:46.340 --> 00:27:50.230
like the one that was
least likely to have ever

00:27:50.230 --> 00:27:52.180
been executed before.

00:27:52.180 --> 00:27:54.600
I'm 100% convinced
that you've never made

00:27:54.600 --> 00:27:59.143
this and it's total bullshit.

00:27:59.143 --> 00:28:02.007
So show us what
you're going to make.

00:28:02.007 --> 00:28:03.840
So Danny's just garnishing
this thing with--

00:28:03.840 --> 00:28:05.890
DANNY BOWIEN: I'm just
garnishing this up.

00:28:05.890 --> 00:28:08.100
So egg-- yeah.

00:28:08.100 --> 00:28:09.210
It's nice.

00:28:09.210 --> 00:28:12.364
You don't have to leave it on
the [? rip, ?] on your stove.

00:28:12.364 --> 00:28:14.030
I think this is longer
than six minutes.

00:28:14.030 --> 00:28:16.980
But what happens is you get
an egg that's really nice.

00:28:16.980 --> 00:28:20.790
Inside the yolk isn't
all brown or grey.

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:21.290
It's nice.

00:28:21.290 --> 00:28:23.137
It's just cooked through.

00:28:23.137 --> 00:28:24.970
Usually it's a little
bit runnier than this.

00:28:24.970 --> 00:28:26.390
But we talked a little too long.

00:28:26.390 --> 00:28:27.010
But yeah.

00:28:27.010 --> 00:28:27.820
It's like that.

00:28:27.820 --> 00:28:29.820
And it peels away really nicely.

00:28:29.820 --> 00:28:30.620
There's egg.

00:28:30.620 --> 00:28:31.240
There's some of
that beef liquid.

00:28:31.240 --> 00:28:32.551
There's some of the beef cheek.

00:28:32.551 --> 00:28:34.550
There's some cilantro and
ginger scallion sauce.

00:28:34.550 --> 00:28:39.766
And then we like to put a nice
big scoop of salmon roe on top.

00:28:39.766 --> 00:28:41.140
CHRIS YING:
Sometimes we do crab.

00:28:41.140 --> 00:28:43.560
But currently crab in
California is poisonous.

00:28:43.560 --> 00:28:45.220
So we didn't do that.

00:28:45.220 --> 00:28:47.889
DANNY BOWIEN: So I'm going
to pass this over to you.

00:28:47.889 --> 00:28:49.180
You can eat this if you'd like.

00:28:49.180 --> 00:28:50.930
CHRIS YING: But everyone
will get a taste.

00:28:50.930 --> 00:28:53.640
I think the kitchen team
is hard at work at that.

00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:55.150
LIV WU: Everybody
will get a taste.

00:28:55.150 --> 00:28:56.040
DANNY BOWIEN: This
makes a noise that

00:28:56.040 --> 00:28:58.460
sounds like it's really bad for
you to stand in front of it.

00:28:58.460 --> 00:28:59.168
Just so you know.

00:28:59.168 --> 00:29:00.360
CHRIS YING: This is Jeff.

00:29:00.360 --> 00:29:00.770
JEFF DALTON: Hi.

00:29:00.770 --> 00:29:02.853
DANNY BOWIEN: Let's give
a hand to Jeff, everyone.

00:29:02.853 --> 00:29:04.510
[APPLAUSE]

00:29:06.860 --> 00:29:07.660
LIV WU: So Jeff--

00:29:07.660 --> 00:29:08.720
CHRIS YING: What are
you making for us?

00:29:08.720 --> 00:29:10.011
JEFF DALTON: So you were right.

00:29:10.011 --> 00:29:11.906
I've never made
this dish before.

00:29:11.906 --> 00:29:12.300
He's completely right.

00:29:12.300 --> 00:29:13.110
I just kind of made it up.

00:29:13.110 --> 00:29:14.930
And actually my friend Alex
over there who's also here--

00:29:14.930 --> 00:29:17.350
we kind of made it up together
at exactly the same time.

00:29:17.350 --> 00:29:19.683
We were just kind of looking
through the Mission Chinese

00:29:19.683 --> 00:29:20.650
stuff that we ate.

00:29:20.650 --> 00:29:22.410
And we were like, what
do we really love?

00:29:22.410 --> 00:29:25.390
We really love the Mapo
tofu that they have.

00:29:25.390 --> 00:29:27.960
And at my house, it's not
Thanksgiving without stuffing.

00:29:27.960 --> 00:29:31.238
So how many of you are going to
have stuffing for Thanksgiving?

00:29:31.238 --> 00:29:32.696
DANNY BOWIEN: Come
on, that's not--

00:29:32.696 --> 00:29:34.570
JEFF DALTON: I think
more of you, hopefully.

00:29:34.570 --> 00:29:35.500
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

