if it's not wet
enough, or-- do you

00:37:05.594 --> 00:37:07.510
like to have your dressing
be more wet or dry?

00:37:07.510 --> 00:37:08.420
JEFF DALTON: That's the
big question, right?

00:37:08.420 --> 00:37:10.090
So how do you like
your dressing?

00:37:10.090 --> 00:37:11.090
Do you like it crunchy?

00:37:11.090 --> 00:37:11.800
Do you like it dry?

00:37:11.800 --> 00:37:12.110
Soggy?

00:37:12.110 --> 00:37:13.330
Some people like it
almost like bread pudding.

00:37:13.330 --> 00:37:14.090
JEFF DALTON: Yeah.

00:37:14.090 --> 00:37:15.340
JEFF DALTON: I like mine
on the crispier side.

00:37:15.340 --> 00:37:16.150
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah, me, too.

00:37:16.150 --> 00:37:18.360
JEFF DALTON: I don't like
it if it gets too soggy.

00:37:18.360 --> 00:37:19.960
It's like eating bread pudding.

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:21.252
And the bread never comes back.

00:37:21.252 --> 00:37:22.710
CHRIS YING: Let me
ask you, though.

00:37:22.710 --> 00:37:24.430
If you're not a Chinese person--

00:37:24.430 --> 00:37:26.650
JEFF DALTON: Yeah.

00:37:26.650 --> 00:37:27.880
DANNY BOWIEN: Theoretically.

00:37:27.880 --> 00:37:29.610
CHRIS YING: And you're
like, oh, family dinner.

00:37:29.610 --> 00:37:30.568
Everyone's coming over.

00:37:30.568 --> 00:37:32.040
All my white
family's coming over.

00:37:32.040 --> 00:37:35.229
And I'm trying to pull out
the Mapo tofu stuffing.

00:37:35.229 --> 00:37:37.270
Are you going to just have
a full-scale rebellion

00:37:37.270 --> 00:37:38.679
on your hands?

00:37:38.679 --> 00:37:40.220
Like, what are you
trying to do here?

00:37:40.220 --> 00:37:41.190
DANNY BOWIEN: I think
if you didn't tell them

00:37:41.190 --> 00:37:41.818
that it's Mapo
tofu stuffing, they

00:37:41.818 --> 00:37:44.100
would just be like, this is
a really delicious stuffing.

00:37:44.100 --> 00:37:45.745
CHRIS YING: But people don't
like their Thanksgivings--

00:37:45.745 --> 00:37:46.060
DANNY BOWIEN: --spicy.

00:37:46.060 --> 00:37:46.520
CHRIS YING: --messed
around with.

00:37:46.520 --> 00:37:47.560
They want Stove Top.

00:37:47.560 --> 00:37:49.742
DANNY BOWIEN: There's no
spice in Thanksgiving.

00:37:49.742 --> 00:37:50.450
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:37:50.450 --> 00:37:53.750
DANNY BOWIEN: It is just a
bunch of butter and sage.

00:37:53.750 --> 00:37:55.140
It's funny.

00:37:55.140 --> 00:37:58.355
Whoever grows sage--
when do you buy sage,

00:37:58.355 --> 00:37:59.415
except for Thanksgiving?

00:37:59.415 --> 00:38:00.790
I always see people
freaking out.

00:38:00.790 --> 00:38:02.164
They're like, do
you have savory?

00:38:02.164 --> 00:38:04.090
Or do you have marjoram?

00:38:04.090 --> 00:38:07.560
That's the one holiday
that the herb growers--

00:38:07.560 --> 00:38:08.310
CHRIS YING: Right.

00:38:08.310 --> 00:38:10.480
If you're a sage
farmer, it's tough times

00:38:10.480 --> 00:38:15.040
until November-- or
a cranberry farmer.

00:38:15.040 --> 00:38:16.130
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:38:16.130 --> 00:38:18.421
I think Thanksgiving should
always be a little spicier,

00:38:18.421 --> 00:38:19.070
personally.

00:38:19.070 --> 00:38:20.340
JEFF DALTON: So
how do you like it?

00:38:20.340 --> 00:38:21.310
DANNY BOWIEN: So
my mom used to make

00:38:21.310 --> 00:38:22.790
stuffing very similar to this.

00:38:22.790 --> 00:38:26.260
She would save--
we'd make cornbread.

00:38:26.260 --> 00:38:28.175
She would save the
leftover cornbread.

00:38:28.175 --> 00:38:29.920
And she would dry that out.

00:38:29.920 --> 00:38:32.370
And she would take Wonder
Bread or white bread

00:38:32.370 --> 00:38:35.660
and dry that out until
it was like that.

00:38:35.660 --> 00:38:39.010
And then she would add a
bunch of dried sage and thyme

00:38:39.010 --> 00:38:40.540
and butter.

00:38:40.540 --> 00:38:43.840
And then she would also take
a box of Stove Top stuffing,

00:38:43.840 --> 00:38:46.000
and then canned chicken stock.

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:48.070
I mean, I grew up in Oklahoma.

00:38:48.070 --> 00:38:52.640
But she would cook
it like a cake.

00:38:52.640 --> 00:38:55.880
And it was very-- you could pick
it up and eat it like pizza.

00:38:55.880 --> 00:38:56.732
It was really cool.

00:38:56.732 --> 00:38:57.440
There was celery.

00:38:57.440 --> 00:38:59.106
It was basically what
you're making now.

00:38:59.106 --> 00:39:02.187
I don't understand how
it's the same thing.

00:39:02.187 --> 00:39:03.520
Hers didn't have any meat in it.

00:39:03.520 --> 00:39:05.670
It just had chicken stock.

00:39:05.670 --> 00:39:08.186
But I like it where you can
just pick it up and eat it

00:39:08.186 --> 00:39:09.390
with your hands.

00:39:09.390 --> 00:39:10.140
JEFF DALTON: Yeah.

00:39:10.140 --> 00:39:11.100
DANNY BOWIEN: I don't think
anyone here has probably ever

00:39:11.100 --> 00:39:12.350
had it that way.

00:39:12.350 --> 00:39:14.440
It's very wrong, but very right.

00:39:14.440 --> 00:39:16.500
I liked it.

00:39:16.500 --> 00:39:18.724
So do you do egg in there?

00:39:18.724 --> 00:39:20.140
JEFF DALTON: I do
do egg in there.

00:39:20.140 --> 00:39:20.800
Yes.

00:39:20.800 --> 00:39:23.710
So eggs are optional.

00:39:23.710 --> 00:39:25.630
Sometimes I don't
like it too eggy.

00:39:25.630 --> 00:39:26.802
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:39:26.802 --> 00:39:27.760
JEFF DALTON: Let's see.

00:39:27.760 --> 00:39:30.051
DANNY BOWIEN: You can just
crack them into here, maybe.

00:39:30.051 --> 00:39:32.330
And then we can stir
this together and then

00:39:32.330 --> 00:39:34.206
stir it back in.

00:39:37.925 --> 00:39:39.716
CHRIS YING: Stuffing's
one of those things.

00:39:39.716 --> 00:39:43.185
I didn't-- I don't know what
it's supposed to look like.

00:39:43.185 --> 00:39:44.754
Like, I don't know
what pot roast is.

00:39:44.754 --> 00:39:45.920
I never had that growing up.

00:39:45.920 --> 00:39:46.950
So I don't know what that's
supposed to look like.

00:39:46.950 --> 00:39:47.930
DANNY BOWIEN: It's
like stew, right?

00:39:47.930 --> 00:39:49.263
CHRIS YING: I've never seen one.

00:39:49.263 --> 00:39:51.354
So it's like, if I try
to make one, I'm like--

00:39:51.354 --> 00:39:52.853
DANNY BOWIEN: Where
did you grow up?

00:39:52.853 --> 00:39:53.501
In California?

00:39:53.501 --> 00:39:55.000
CHRIS YING: I grew
up in California.

00:39:55.000 --> 00:39:56.000
DANNY BOWIEN: All right.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:39:58.370
Does everyone else in here
know what pot roast is?

00:39:58.370 --> 00:39:58.870
Oh.

00:39:58.870 --> 00:39:59.240
It's stew.

00:39:59.240 --> 00:40:00.740
CHRIS YING: There's
Asian people who

00:40:00.740 --> 00:40:01.990
don't know what pot roast is.

00:40:01.990 --> 00:40:03.915
We have no idea
what pot roast is.

00:40:03.915 --> 00:40:07.240
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah, but
there's-- yeah, you're right.

00:40:07.240 --> 00:40:07.740
So anyways.

00:40:07.740 --> 00:40:08.710
The egg goes in.

00:40:08.710 --> 00:40:08.890
Mix it all up.

00:40:08.890 --> 00:40:10.556
JEFF DALTON: Mix it
with a little broth,

00:40:10.556 --> 00:40:12.820
so you don't get little
bits of egg, maybe.

00:40:12.820 --> 00:40:14.500
DANNY BOWIEN: Are you-- do
you own a restaurant somewhere

00:40:14.500 --> 00:40:15.595
or something like this?

00:40:15.595 --> 00:40:15.898
CHRIS YING: Dude.

00:40:15.898 --> 00:40:16.856
You're killing it, man.

00:40:19.760 --> 00:40:21.260
DANNY BOWIEN: And
then you just want

00:40:21.260 --> 00:40:22.511
to bake it until it just sets.

00:40:22.511 --> 00:40:24.010
JEFF DALTON: Bake
it until it's set,

00:40:24.010 --> 00:40:26.250
until the top gets a little
nice and golden brown.

00:40:26.250 --> 00:40:27.640
Make sure it's crispy.

00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:29.085
And I think that's about it.

00:40:29.085 --> 00:40:30.043
DANNY BOWIEN: Oh, cool.

00:40:30.043 --> 00:40:33.040
JEFF DALTON: So I think it's
maybe about 45 minutes at 350

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:34.582
degrees.

00:40:34.582 --> 00:40:36.040
CHRIS YING: Let's
actually stick it

00:40:36.040 --> 00:40:37.490
in the oven so it's
done by the time we're

00:40:37.490 --> 00:40:38.670
done signing books and stuff.

00:40:38.670 --> 00:40:39.200
JEFF DALTON: Sounds good to me.

00:40:39.200 --> 00:40:41.590
LIV WU: So while we wait for
that, are there questions?

00:40:41.590 --> 00:40:42.580
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:40:42.580 --> 00:40:43.330
Who has questions?

00:40:43.330 --> 00:40:44.270
LIV WU: Questions
from out there?

00:40:44.270 --> 00:40:45.520
DANNY BOWIEN: Hey thanks, man.

00:40:45.520 --> 00:40:46.630
Let's give a nice--

00:40:46.630 --> 00:40:47.588
JEFF DALTON: Thank you.

00:40:47.588 --> 00:40:49.130
[APPLAUSE]

00:40:54.833 --> 00:40:55.770
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:40:55.770 --> 00:40:56.630
DANNY BOWIEN: We
can take heat, too.

00:40:56.630 --> 00:40:57.240
So ask us.

00:40:57.240 --> 00:40:59.640
You can ask us very
uncomfortable questions.

00:40:59.640 --> 00:41:03.170
Please don't ask the
following questions.

00:41:03.170 --> 00:41:04.939
What's your favorite restaurant?

00:41:04.939 --> 00:41:06.730
So hopefully you weren't
going to ask that.

00:41:06.730 --> 00:41:07.080
AUDIENCE: No.

00:41:07.080 --> 00:41:08.277
DANNY BOWIEN: Please don't
ask New York versus San

00:41:08.277 --> 00:41:10.490
Francisco, because I'm
not going to answer that.

00:41:10.490 --> 00:41:12.726
And also, please don't
ask the last thing

00:41:12.726 --> 00:41:14.310
I would eat before I die.

00:41:14.310 --> 00:41:16.647
Because hopefully I
don't die anytime soon.

00:41:16.647 --> 00:41:18.480
Those are the only--
other than that, if you

00:41:18.480 --> 00:41:20.096
want to ask anything else.

00:41:20.096 --> 00:41:20.720
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:41:20.720 --> 00:41:22.511
So I had a chance to
eat at your restaurant

00:41:22.511 --> 00:41:23.970
in New York in the last month.

00:41:23.970 --> 00:41:24.580
It was great.

00:41:24.580 --> 00:41:25.371
DANNY BOWIEN: Cool.

00:41:25.371 --> 00:41:27.230
AUDIENCE: So I
had two questions.

00:41:27.230 --> 00:41:31.350
Can you tell us the story behind
how pizza made it to the menu?

00:41:31.350 --> 00:41:33.140
And then, did you
ever find it ironic

00:41:33.140 --> 00:41:36.227
that beggar's duck costs $100?

00:41:36.227 --> 00:41:38.310
DANNY BOWIEN: Well, to
answer your first question,

00:41:38.310 --> 00:41:40.070
pizza got on the menu when
we moved into the restaurant

00:41:40.070 --> 00:41:40.569
in New York.

00:41:40.569 --> 00:41:45.890
The space is like--
everyone here

00:41:45.890 --> 00:41:47.720
has been to Nopa before, right?

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:48.680
It's bigger than that.

00:41:48.680 --> 00:41:52.180
So the restaurant before
was like 40 seats.

00:41:52.180 --> 00:41:53.630
And it was in a
1,000 square foot

00:41:53.630 --> 00:41:55.819
space in the Lower East Side.

00:41:55.819 --> 00:41:57.610
And then now it's like--
I don't even know.

00:41:57.610 --> 00:41:58.930
It's very, very big.

00:41:58.930 --> 00:42:00.810
It's like 140-plus seats.

00:42:00.810 --> 00:42:02.550
Plus we have a
private dining room.

00:42:02.550 --> 00:42:05.240
So when we moved in-- this
had been a restaurant before.

00:42:05.240 --> 00:42:06.780
And there was a
brick oven there.

00:42:06.780 --> 00:42:09.720
And for me, we always--
when we reopened

00:42:09.720 --> 00:42:13.690
Mission Chinese in
New York, I had a lot

00:42:13.690 --> 00:42:15.370
to prove to myself personally.

00:42:15.370 --> 00:42:17.880
But also I was so
tired of living

00:42:17.880 --> 00:42:22.150
by the guidelines of just
being in fear of failure.

00:42:22.150 --> 00:42:24.672
Because I'd clearly already
just failed the worst way

00:42:24.672 --> 00:42:26.520
you could possibly
fail as a chef.

00:42:26.520 --> 00:42:28.729
So when I opened up
again, I was like,

00:42:28.729 --> 00:42:30.020
I'm just doing this for me now.

00:42:30.020 --> 00:42:31.470
I'm not doing it
for the critics.

00:42:31.470 --> 00:42:32.770
I don't give a shit
what anyone else thinks.

00:42:32.770 --> 00:42:34.730
If I know that it's good, and
it's something that I really

00:42:34.730 --> 00:42:36.450
love and like-- and that's
what food and cooking is all

00:42:36.450 --> 00:42:38.300
about anyways-- then
I want to make it.

00:42:38.300 --> 00:42:40.030
And then hopefully
that happiness

00:42:40.030 --> 00:42:42.800
that I'm projecting
into this dish

00:42:42.800 --> 00:42:47.200
will translate to people
that are eating it.

00:42:47.200 --> 00:42:48.750
And also, because
not everyone wants

00:42:48.750 --> 00:42:50.349
to eat Sichuan
food all the time.

00:42:50.349 --> 00:42:52.390
So a lot of kids would
come in, and their friends

00:42:52.390 --> 00:42:54.300
would come in, to
the old restaurant.

00:42:54.300 --> 00:42:56.090
Say David Chang comes in.

00:42:56.090 --> 00:42:57.940
And he's eaten at the
restaurant before.

00:42:57.940 --> 00:43:01.510
What can we give him that he's
definitely not going to expect?

00:43:01.510 --> 00:43:03.250
We do this to
friends all the time.

00:43:03.250 --> 00:43:05.180
So we used to just
order a bunch of pizza

00:43:05.180 --> 00:43:07.100
at the original
Mission Chinese Food.

00:43:07.100 --> 00:43:09.200
And if you came in, at
the end of your meal,

00:43:09.200 --> 00:43:10.090
instead of sending
you dessert, we'd

00:43:10.090 --> 00:43:12.000
just drop a whole
pepperoni pizza on you.

00:43:12.000 --> 00:43:15.020
And it's kind of like a
smartass way for chefs

00:43:15.020 --> 00:43:16.420
to torture each other.

00:43:16.420 --> 00:43:20.560
But also it was like, well, if
you come in with your family

00:43:20.560 --> 00:43:22.450
and your six-year-old
is there, they

00:43:22.450 --> 00:43:24.664
can't eat ripping
hot chicken wings.

00:43:24.664 --> 00:43:26.080
We should be able
to make a pizza.

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:28.070
So then as a chef, we
just obsessed on that.

00:43:28.070 --> 00:43:30.260
And I was like, I really
love Naples-style pizza.

00:43:30.260 --> 00:43:35.350
I really admire what
Anthony does at Una Pizza

00:43:35.350 --> 00:43:38.040
Napoletana in San Francisco.

00:43:38.040 --> 00:43:42.180
So I called Chad Robertson
up from Tartine Bakery.

00:43:42.180 --> 00:43:45.254
And I was like, hey, I
want to make the sickest,

00:43:45.254 --> 00:43:47.670
authentic-- this is the only
authentic thing I want to do.

00:43:47.670 --> 00:43:50.640
I want to make a real,
true, Naples-style pizza.

00:43:50.640 --> 00:43:53.190
But I want to use the Tartine
Bakery sourdough starter.

00:43:53.190 --> 00:43:54.237
Can you make that happen?

00:43:54.237 --> 00:43:55.070
Chad's very excited.

00:43:55.070 --> 00:43:55.920
He comes out.

00:43:55.920 --> 00:43:57.877
He flies up from San
Francisco to New York.

00:43:57.877 --> 00:43:58.960
And he's like, here's how.

00:43:58.960 --> 00:43:59.469
Let's do it.

00:43:59.469 --> 00:44:00.260
Here's our starter.

00:44:00.260 --> 00:44:02.420
So we put together
this dough recipe.

00:44:02.420 --> 00:44:05.510
All the ingredients that go on
that pizza are certified DOP.

00:44:05.510 --> 00:44:08.700
So it's San Marzano
tomatoes, buffalo mozzarella

00:44:08.700 --> 00:44:10.060
from [? Concerta ?].

00:44:10.060 --> 00:44:14.090
Everything is basically from
Naples that goes on that pizza.

00:44:14.090 --> 00:44:15.647
But in true Mission
Chinese fashion,

00:44:15.647 --> 00:44:17.730
if you want to just throw
all that out the window,

00:44:17.730 --> 00:44:19.730
we'll throw a pepperoni
on it for you for $0.99.

00:44:19.730 --> 00:44:21.280
So that's how that
dish came about.

00:44:21.280 --> 00:44:23.380
And it's still my favorite
thing on the menu.

00:44:23.380 --> 00:44:24.710
I eat it like once a week.

00:44:24.710 --> 00:44:26.460
CHRIS YING: But when Dave came
in, the first thing he did--

00:44:26.460 --> 00:44:28.020
DANNY BOWIEN: Oh, and
then David Chang comes in,

00:44:28.020 --> 00:44:29.320
and just is like, oh.

00:44:29.320 --> 00:44:31.944
So DOP is like-- I don't know if
you guys know what that means.

00:44:31.944 --> 00:44:34.410
But it's kind of like
this stamp of approval

00:44:34.410 --> 00:44:38.020
that's given to certain
foodstuffs in Italy.

00:44:38.020 --> 00:44:41.834
So it's basically
a mark of quality.

00:44:41.834 --> 00:44:43.250
So like in the
US-- it's like when

00:44:43.250 --> 00:44:47.760
people call champagne champagne,
it has to come from Champagne.

00:44:47.760 --> 00:44:50.680
It has to be a certain-- there's
all these specifications it

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:51.510
has to meet.

00:44:51.510 --> 00:44:55.090
They do the same thing in Italy
with prosciutto, mozzarella--

00:44:55.090 --> 00:44:56.420
CHRIS YING: Parmesan.

00:44:56.420 --> 00:44:58.070
DANNY BOWIEN:
Parmesan, especially.

00:44:58.070 --> 00:45:03.170
So it's all protected by
this stamp of approval.

00:45:03.170 --> 00:45:05.320
So a lot of restaurants,
if you go to a restaurant,

00:45:05.320 --> 00:45:06.904
it's like DOP this or DOP that.

00:45:06.904 --> 00:45:08.570
You know it's just
the best of the best.

00:45:08.570 --> 00:45:09.560
David Chang comes in.

00:45:09.560 --> 00:45:10.750
And the first thing
he does is just

00:45:10.750 --> 00:45:11.916
dump Mapo tofu on his pizza.

00:45:11.916 --> 00:45:14.640
He's like, this is
going to be amazing.

00:45:14.640 --> 00:45:16.370
He puts that on Instagram.

00:45:16.370 --> 00:45:17.640
CHRIS YING: One of the
ugliest Instagram photos.

00:45:17.640 --> 00:45:19.100
DANNY BOWIEN: I can't
tell you how many people

00:45:19.100 --> 00:45:20.320
came in asking for that.

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:22.350
And they would
order the Mapo tofu.

00:45:22.350 --> 00:45:24.310
Can I get that when
the pizza comes out?

00:45:24.310 --> 00:45:27.690
And they pour it on top.

00:45:27.690 --> 00:45:30.890
And then your second question,
which I forgot already--

00:45:30.890 --> 00:45:32.286
what was your second question?

00:45:32.286 --> 00:45:34.516
AUDIENCE: It was, did
you find it ironic

00:45:34.516 --> 00:45:36.680
that beggar's duck costs $100?

00:45:36.680 --> 00:45:38.970
DANNY BOWIEN: So I think
that's a good question.

00:45:38.970 --> 00:45:42.150
Because I don't find it ironic
that beggar's duck costs $100.

00:45:42.150 --> 00:45:44.364
Because I think if
you go to R&amp;G Lounge--

00:45:44.364 --> 00:45:45.780
the first time I
ever-- I've never

00:45:45.780 --> 00:45:48.050
actually had beggar's
chicken before.

00:45:48.050 --> 00:45:50.100
That dish is in
the book, actually.

00:45:50.100 --> 00:45:52.070
And that's a riff on
beggar's chicken, which

00:45:52.070 --> 00:45:55.980
is a whole chicken that's
stuffed inside of a lotus leaf

00:45:55.980 --> 00:45:57.530
and clay and then baked.

00:45:57.530 --> 00:46:01.790
And the idea behind that
is it was a peasant dish.

00:46:01.790 --> 00:46:05.790
The fable was that there was
a beggar out in the streets.

00:46:05.790 --> 00:46:08.140
And the emperor
walked by and smelled

00:46:08.140 --> 00:46:09.669
this beautiful, wonderful smell.

00:46:09.669 --> 00:46:11.710
And this beggar had just
gotten this chicken that

00:46:11.710 --> 00:46:13.725
was thrown to them, and
wrapped it in lotus and clay,

00:46:13.725 --> 00:46:15.520
and threw it into a
fire and roasted it.

00:46:15.520 --> 00:46:17.040
And then I guess--

00:46:17.040 --> 00:46:18.780
CHRIS YING: Well,
so it's not ironic.

00:46:18.780 --> 00:46:20.467
Because first of all--

00:46:20.467 --> 00:46:22.800
DANNY BOWIEN: So then he was
like, this is so delicious.

00:46:22.800 --> 00:46:25.650
And it became part
of the staple--

00:46:25.650 --> 00:46:27.081
am I fucking this story up?

00:46:27.081 --> 00:46:28.080
Is this the right story?

00:46:28.080 --> 00:46:28.350
CHRIS YING: A little bit.

00:46:28.350 --> 00:46:28.550
DANNY BOWIEN: All right.

00:46:28.550 --> 00:46:29.580
Anyways, somebody
Wikipedia that.

00:46:29.580 --> 00:46:30.420
Or Google it.

00:46:33.900 --> 00:46:37.230
CHRIS YING: First of all,
the whole apocryphal story

00:46:37.230 --> 00:46:40.757
is the beggar had a duck but he
didn't have a way to cook it.

00:46:40.757 --> 00:46:43.090
So he covered it in mud and
clay and cooked it that way.

00:46:43.090 --> 00:46:44.548
It was the only
way he could do it.

00:46:44.548 --> 00:46:46.391
And he didn't want
the juices and smells

00:46:46.391 --> 00:46:48.390
and everything escaping
so people would take it.

00:46:48.390 --> 00:46:52.120
So the whole idea is that
this is a very valuable thing.

00:46:52.120 --> 00:46:54.580
And you want to
cook it as carefully

00:46:54.580 --> 00:46:56.700
and protect it as
much as you can.

00:46:56.700 --> 00:46:58.850
And then, it's not
ironic that it's

00:46:58.850 --> 00:47:00.910
$100 because I
tested that recipe.

00:47:00.910 --> 00:47:02.940
It is a fucking pain in
the ass to make that.

00:47:02.940 --> 00:47:06.500
DANNY BOWIEN: Beyond all that,
if you go-- at your house,

00:47:06.500 --> 00:47:09.060
if you go to buy a
really nice duck, that's

00:47:09.060 --> 00:47:11.910
going to set you back, I
would say, $30 minimally.

00:47:11.910 --> 00:47:14.700
If you buy enough duck fat
to confit a whole duck in,

00:47:14.700 --> 00:47:16.530
that's going to set you back--

00:47:16.530 --> 00:47:17.769
CHRIS YING: $60 more.

00:47:17.769 --> 00:47:19.560
DANNY BOWIEN: So it's
actually cheaper just

00:47:19.560 --> 00:47:20.350
to come to the restaurant.

00:47:20.350 --> 00:47:22.391
That dish actually is
cheaper just to come eat it

00:47:22.391 --> 00:47:23.394
at the restaurant.

00:47:23.394 --> 00:47:25.560
CHRIS YING: If that beggar
could make a business out

00:47:25.560 --> 00:47:26.520
of selling his duck--

00:47:26.520 --> 00:47:26.910
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:47:26.910 --> 00:47:28.535
It should just be
called Beggar's Duck.

00:47:28.535 --> 00:47:30.508
That's the next restaurant
we're going to open.

00:47:30.508 --> 00:47:31.258
AUDIENCE: Awesome.

00:47:31.258 --> 00:47:31.758
Thank you.

00:47:31.758 --> 00:47:33.280
DANNY BOWIEN: Anyways.

00:47:33.280 --> 00:47:34.770
AUDIENCE: Thanks for coming.

00:47:34.770 --> 00:47:37.040
How did you two meet?

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:39.822
DANNY BOWIEN: Well
so we met-- I always

00:47:39.822 --> 00:47:41.696
say the most inappropriate
things when people

00:47:41.696 --> 00:47:44.530
will say how did you meet.

00:47:44.530 --> 00:47:49.260
But the true story is that we
met at Mission Street Food.

00:47:49.260 --> 00:47:53.080
And we met through Anthony
Myint, my other half

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:54.320
of Mission Chinese.

00:47:54.320 --> 00:47:56.530
And Chris-- I thought
Chris was a line cook.

00:47:56.530 --> 00:47:58.540
Because at Mission
Street Food, it

00:47:58.540 --> 00:48:01.190
would be these guest chefs
that would come in every week.

00:48:01.190 --> 00:48:02.874
And I was just helping out.

00:48:02.874 --> 00:48:04.540
So you would just
meet different people.

00:48:04.540 --> 00:48:07.080
And I would see, Chris would
just always kind of be there.

00:48:07.080 --> 00:48:09.776
So I thought he was a chef
or a cook for so long.

00:48:09.776 --> 00:48:11.150
Because he knew
how to line cook.

00:48:11.150 --> 00:48:12.566
And we would help
other chefs out.

00:48:12.566 --> 00:48:16.116
But that was like-- how long
did I think you were a cook?

00:48:16.116 --> 00:48:17.490
Until you were
like, oh, actually

00:48:17.490 --> 00:48:18.810
I work for "McSweeney's"
at the time.

00:48:18.810 --> 00:48:19.580
And I'm a writer.

00:48:19.580 --> 00:48:20.060
CHRIS YING: Yeah.

00:48:20.060 --> 00:48:21.250
Probably for like six
months we were cooking next

00:48:21.250 --> 00:48:21.834
to each other.

00:48:21.834 --> 00:48:23.999
And then maybe when I was
like, we should do a book,

00:48:23.999 --> 00:48:26.150
he was like, what do you
mean we should do a book?

00:48:26.150 --> 00:48:27.510
I thought you-- are you
a writer or something?

00:48:27.510 --> 00:48:28.830
I was like, oh, I
just come here--

00:48:28.830 --> 00:48:31.371
DANNY BOWIEN: He just comes here
every Thursday to help cook.

00:48:31.371 --> 00:48:34.810
And then all the other days
of the week he had a real job.

00:48:34.810 --> 00:48:35.790
So that's how we met.

00:48:40.620 --> 00:48:43.840
AUDIENCE: I want to preface
this question by saying I really

00:48:43.840 --> 00:48:45.910
like cooking with MSG.

00:48:45.910 --> 00:48:49.335
My question is, one, is
there MSG on the tortillas

00:48:49.335 --> 00:48:50.772
at Mission Cantina?

00:48:50.772 --> 00:48:51.480
DANNY BOWIEN: No.

00:48:51.480 --> 00:48:53.520
AUDIENCE: And two,
what role do you think

00:48:53.520 --> 00:48:55.586
MSG should play in the kitchen?

00:48:55.586 --> 00:48:57.710
DANNY BOWIEN: I think it
should play-- so you know,

00:48:57.710 --> 00:48:59.960
Anthony Bourdain asked me
this question the other day.

00:48:59.960 --> 00:49:03.940
I am not really
one to ever say--

00:49:03.940 --> 00:49:05.330
I don't like living
by absolutes.

00:49:05.330 --> 00:49:08.740
So if you want to
use MSG, use MSG.

00:49:08.740 --> 00:49:12.190
If people-- if you like that--
I understand economically,

00:49:12.190 --> 00:49:14.990
for some restaurants and
restaurateurs and restaurant

00:49:14.990 --> 00:49:17.980
owners, if you have a
restaurant that's selling a rice

00:49:17.980 --> 00:49:21.194
plate for like $5, and it's
a whole duck leg on rice,

00:49:21.194 --> 00:49:22.860
and there's some MSG
on there to make it

00:49:22.860 --> 00:49:27.830
taste a little better or
whatever, that's on you.

00:49:27.830 --> 00:49:30.840
I don't think there's a right or
wrong way, unless it's harmful.

00:49:30.840 --> 00:49:34.720
Which it has not been
proven harmful to your body.

00:49:34.720 --> 00:49:36.584
We don't use MSG
in the restaurants.

00:49:36.584 --> 00:49:38.875
No, there's no MSG on the
chips on the chips at Mission

00:49:38.875 --> 00:49:39.540
Cantina.

00:49:39.540 --> 00:49:41.916
Although now that you say
that, there probably should be.

00:49:41.916 --> 00:49:43.831
We can get away with it
there because it's not

00:49:43.831 --> 00:49:45.060
a Chinese restaurant.

00:49:45.060 --> 00:49:46.768
CHRIS YING: It's like
a shortcut, though.

00:49:46.768 --> 00:49:48.768
It's like a different way
of getting to a thing.

00:49:48.768 --> 00:49:49.559
DANNY BOWIEN: Yeah.

00:49:49.559 --> 00:49:51.670
It basically shortens
the path of-- you know,

00:49:51.670 --> 00:49:54.500
when you take something like
a beef cheek, for instance,

00:49:54.500 --> 00:49:56.700
and you sear it and
you braise it really

00:49:56.700 --> 00:50:00.960
slowly in stock, what happens
is you're basically pulling out

00:50:00.960 --> 00:50:02.940
lots of umami.

00:50:02.940 --> 00:50:04.320
When you sear
something-- there's

00:50:04.320 --> 00:50:08.110
a lot of technical terms
to explain why things taste

00:50:08.110 --> 00:50:09.360
better when you sear them.

00:50:09.360 --> 00:50:12.520
There's like a Maillard reaction
where protein actually converts

00:50:12.520 --> 00:50:14.470
to flavor when you sear it.

00:50:14.470 --> 00:50:17.730
But long story short is
MSG is just a shortcut

00:50:17.730 --> 00:50:22.290
to get that very unctuous
umami flavor that you

00:50:22.290 --> 00:50:25.790
get when you cook a bolognese
sauce for like six hours.

00:50:25.790 --> 00:50:27.825
You can just saute
some meat in a pan,

00:50:27.825 --> 00:50:29.200
put some tomatoes
there, and MSG,

00:50:29.200 --> 00:50:31.620
and it will taste pretty good.

00:50:31.620 --> 00:50:35.300
So I think that MSG plays
a role in lots of things.

00:50:35.300 --> 00:50:36.840
You know, it's funny.

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:39.710
I've always thought Chinese
food gets this bad rap

00:50:39.710 --> 00:50:41.620
for using MSG.

00:50:41.620 --> 00:50:45.415
If you go to Japan,
which is also

00:50:45.415 --> 00:50:47.040
one of my favorite
places in the world,

00:50:47.040 --> 00:50:48.831
there's MSG in some of
their sports drinks.

00:50:48.831 --> 00:50:52.300
There's MSG in like
everything in Japan.

00:50:52.300 --> 00:50:55.290
But no one ever says
anything about that.

00:50:55.290 --> 00:50:56.620
And I don't understand why.

00:50:56.620 --> 00:50:58.120
Because it's not
really a bad thing.

00:50:58.120 --> 00:51:01.274
All the pickles that you
get at Japanese restaurants,

00:51:01.274 --> 00:51:02.440
usually there's MSG in them.

00:51:02.440 --> 00:51:06.660
There's NutraSweet in a lot
of pickles in Korea and Japan.

00:51:06.660 --> 00:51:09.270
Because when you add
that as a sweetener,

00:51:09.270 --> 00:51:12.060
it actually gives it a
different crunch and your palate

00:51:12.060 --> 00:51:14.680
registers it different
than just sugar or salt.

00:51:14.680 --> 00:51:17.400
So I mean, again, it's
not like I'm saying

00:51:17.400 --> 00:51:18.510
go home and cook with MSG.

00:51:18.510 --> 00:51:21.180
But if you buy the book
and you're like, hey,

00:51:21.180 --> 00:51:22.680
I want to do this
and this and this,

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:25.013
am I going to get mad at you
if you put MSG in the food?

00:51:25.013 --> 00:51:25.765
I don't care.

00:51:25.765 --> 00:51:26.390
It's your food.

00:51:28.930 --> 00:51:30.060
It's not evil.

00:51:30.060 --> 00:51:31.830
I guess that's the--

00:51:31.830 --> 00:51:32.500
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:51:32.500 --> 00:51:33.640
Oh.

00:51:33.640 --> 00:51:35.370
Hello.

00:51:35.370 --> 00:51:38.310
Can you talk about the process,
or the thought process,

00:51:38.310 --> 00:51:40.310
that you go through when
you create a new dish?

00:51:40.310 --> 00:51:42.320
Is it like, oh, I
have this flavor.

00:51:42.320 --> 00:51:43.450
What can I do with it?

00:51:43.450 --> 00:51:44.200
Or is it like, oh.

00:51:44.200 --> 00:51:45.070
Do you take something.

00:51:45.070 --> 00:51:46.778
You're like, what can
I do to improve it?

00:51:46.778 --> 00:51:49.432
Can you walk us through
how the process starts

00:51:49.432 --> 00:51:51.140
and how you take it
from start to finish?

00:51:51.140 --> 00:51:51.931
DANNY BOWIEN: Sure.

00:51:51.931 --> 00:51:54.910
So luckily enough now,
we're five years in.

00:51:54.910 --> 00:51:57.470
So we're actually
surrounded by lots of really

00:51:57.470 --> 00:51:59.950
great young cooks and chefs.

00:51:59.950 --> 00:52:03.124
And usually the
thought-- the idea

00:52:03.124 --> 00:52:04.790
in the beginning of
Mission Chinese Food

00:52:04.790 --> 00:52:06.956
is like, I just want to
figure out how to make this.

00:52:06.956 --> 00:52:11.210
So I would just go eat at
Spices II in San Francisco.

00:52:11.210 --> 00:52:13.520
And I would eat there and
have all these crazy dishes,

00:52:13.520 --> 00:52:16.300
like pig ears tureen in like
tingling oil and Mapo tofu.

00:52:16.300 --> 00:52:17.800
And that would serve
as inspiration.

00:52:17.800 --> 00:52:20.052
Then sometimes, in
the very beginning,

00:52:20.052 --> 00:52:21.260
that was the thought process.

00:52:21.260 --> 00:52:22.699
I'd be like, how
do I decode this?

00:52:22.699 --> 00:52:24.490
Because no one's going
to give me a recipe.

00:52:24.490 --> 00:52:26.720
It's not like--
five years ago, you

00:52:26.720 --> 00:52:32.600
couldn't really look up a recipe
for tingling pig intestine.

00:52:32.600 --> 00:52:33.950
You can't really find that.

00:52:33.950 --> 00:52:36.890
So then I think now,
where we're at now

00:52:36.890 --> 00:52:39.680
is like we'll get an item.

00:52:39.680 --> 00:52:42.310
It could be like we'll have
a good meal at a restaurant

00:52:42.310 --> 00:52:45.510
and get inspired by just how
someone's plating something.

00:52:45.510 --> 00:52:48.840
Or you'll get a dish
like koji, for instance.

00:52:48.840 --> 00:52:53.490
We use koji, which is a
culture that's made with rice.

00:52:53.490 --> 00:52:55.860
And it's been used
in Japan forever.

00:52:55.860 --> 00:52:59.370
But we will cure things in that.

00:52:59.370 --> 00:53:00.440
That's a good example.

00:53:00.440 --> 00:53:04.120
So the koji fried
chicken in the book-- we

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:05.440
had this koji culture.

00:53:05.440 --> 00:53:06.500
And we were like,
how can we use this?

00:53:06.500 --> 00:53:07.500
And how do we make this?

00:53:07.500 --> 00:53:09.710
And what is this
thing all about?

00:53:09.710 --> 00:53:13.530
And that kind of informed--
it was like, well,

00:53:13.530 --> 00:53:16.320
I've always wanted to make the
best [? Hunanese ?] chicken.

00:53:16.320 --> 00:53:17.372
That's my favorite dish.

00:53:17.372 --> 00:53:19.580
But I don't think that a
lot of people get that dish.

00:53:19.580 --> 00:53:21.580
Because [? Hunanese ?]
chicken is chicken that's

00:53:21.580 --> 00:53:23.710
just been poached perfectly.

00:53:23.710 --> 00:53:25.310
And then it's
usually served cold

00:53:25.310 --> 00:53:27.540
with the liquid that
it was cooked in

00:53:27.540 --> 00:53:30.700
and some rice and
ginger scallion sauce.

00:53:30.700 --> 00:53:32.824
So that process was like,
let's try to use koji.

00:53:32.824 --> 00:53:34.948
Let's try to make fried
chicken without dredging it

00:53:34.948 --> 00:53:39.807
in anything, with super crispy
skin, that's gluten free.

00:53:39.807 --> 00:53:41.390
So you're not putting
any flour on it.

00:53:41.390 --> 00:53:42.610
And let's make it taste
like [? Hunanese ?] chicken

00:53:42.610 --> 00:53:44.650
because that's my favorite
thing in the world.

00:53:44.650 --> 00:53:47.450
So it's kind of
like a super-ADHD--

00:53:47.450 --> 00:53:49.840
like, this is a good idea.

00:53:49.840 --> 00:53:51.780
And then this is
also a good idea.

00:53:51.780 --> 00:53:53.150
And hopefully this all works.

00:53:53.150 --> 00:53:59.000
But we've been chasing
after trying to recreate

00:53:59.000 --> 00:53:59.940
a lot of other things.

00:53:59.940 --> 00:54:02.670
The worst thing you can do
when you're thinking of recipes

00:54:02.670 --> 00:54:04.820
or having a through
process is trying

00:54:04.820 --> 00:54:06.790
to match something
you've done before.

00:54:06.790 --> 00:54:08.410
I think that for
the longest time,

00:54:08.410 --> 00:54:10.300
I was like, how do we make
another thrice-cooked bacon?

00:54:10.300 --> 00:54:12.091
How do we make another
salt cod fried rice?

00:54:12.091 --> 00:54:14.750
How do we make another
sick version of Mapo tofu?

00:54:14.750 --> 00:54:18.330
And after a while, it was
just like, how can we just

00:54:18.330 --> 00:54:22.900
stay with this and kind of just
push ourselves further ahead?

00:54:22.900 --> 00:54:25.290
So I think the thought
process now isn't so much just

00:54:25.290 --> 00:54:28.790
trying to decode classic
Chinese dishes as it is just

00:54:28.790 --> 00:54:32.740
trying to create our own
vocabulary, our own kind

00:54:32.740 --> 00:54:34.060
of food.

00:54:34.060 --> 00:54:38.005
Which is like-- yeah, beggar's
duck and koji fried chicken

00:54:38.005 --> 00:54:38.660
and stuff.

00:54:38.660 --> 00:54:40.124
So that's it.

00:54:40.124 --> 00:54:41.790
LIV WU: We'll have a
last question here.

00:54:41.790 --> 00:54:42.776
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:54:42.776 --> 00:54:43.660
This is super-weird.

00:54:43.660 --> 00:54:44.495
Like-- no.

00:54:44.495 --> 00:54:45.350
Thanks for coming.

00:54:45.350 --> 00:54:45.790
DANNY BOWIEN: No, it's good.

00:54:45.790 --> 00:54:46.270
You don't have to use the mic.

00:54:46.270 --> 00:54:47.550
We can just hang out right here.

00:54:47.550 --> 00:54:48.091
AUDIENCE: No.

00:54:48.091 --> 00:54:50.010
I'm just reading a
lot on food blogs

00:54:50.010 --> 00:54:54.400
and reading diaries about
chefs and their crazy nights

00:54:54.400 --> 00:54:54.910
and stuff.

00:54:54.910 --> 00:54:56.702
I feel like I just hear
these crazy stories

00:54:56.702 --> 00:54:58.993
of other famous chefs showing
up to other famous chefs'

00:54:58.993 --> 00:54:59.600
restaurants.

00:54:59.600 --> 00:55:01.770
And I guess I'm
just wondering, when

00:55:01.770 --> 00:55:03.840
do these relationships
start developing?

00:55:03.840 --> 00:55:05.900
Is there a point
where David Chang

00:55:05.900 --> 00:55:07.695
drives up to a new
chef's restaurant

00:55:07.695 --> 00:55:09.300
and inducts him into a secret--

00:55:09.300 --> 00:55:10.880
DANNY BOWIEN: You pee your
pants when that happens.

00:55:10.880 --> 00:55:13.005
AUDIENCE: Like a secret
fraternity of restaurants--

00:55:13.005 --> 00:55:14.680
they give you the
keys or like a cloak.

00:55:14.680 --> 00:55:16.455
What's going on in
that secret circle?

00:55:16.455 --> 00:55:16.710
DANNY BOWIEN: Nah.

00:55:16.710 --> 00:55:18.840
Usually you just make them eat
pizza at the end of their meal

00:55:18.840 --> 00:55:19.880
and they get mad at you.

00:55:19.880 --> 00:55:21.921
No, I mean, it's like any
other industry, really.

00:55:21.921 --> 00:55:25.570
Especially the food
world-- I'm very fortunate.

00:55:25.570 --> 00:55:28.824
I, five years ago, was
just on every one of these

00:55:28.824 --> 00:55:31.490
chef's-- my favorite chefs-- and
I still am-- on their websites.

00:55:31.490 --> 00:55:32.531
What's David Chang up to?

00:55:32.531 --> 00:55:34.720
What's [? Dan Boulud ?] up to?

00:55:34.720 --> 00:55:37.390
But it is a very tight-knit
community of people.

00:55:37.390 --> 00:55:40.662
And it's also still a
very blue-collar job.

00:55:40.662 --> 00:55:41.620
We're not saving lives.

00:55:41.620 --> 00:55:42.650
We're cooking food.

00:55:42.650 --> 00:55:45.920
So there's a lot of
work that goes into it.

00:55:45.920 --> 00:55:50.130
I think that because of
working 90 hours a week

00:55:50.130 --> 00:55:52.460
on like a restaurant
or whatever,

00:55:52.460 --> 00:55:54.110
everyone just kind
of gets each other.

00:55:54.110 --> 00:55:57.040
And so any spare moment
of time you have,

00:55:57.040 --> 00:55:59.552
when you meet someone
that's a chef you look up to

00:55:59.552 --> 00:56:01.080
or anything, you
always just want

00:56:01.080 --> 00:56:04.130
to try to make that
time count, and make

00:56:04.130 --> 00:56:05.830
it the best time for them ever.

00:56:05.830 --> 00:56:07.499
At a restaurant,
that's what my job is.

00:56:07.499 --> 00:56:09.165
It's to make sure
that when you come in,

00:56:09.165 --> 00:56:11.140
you just have an amazing time.

00:56:11.140 --> 00:56:13.866
And you leave happier
than you-- ideally, you

00:56:13.866 --> 00:56:15.740
leave happier than you
were when you came in.

00:56:15.740 --> 00:56:16.800
And fuller.

00:56:16.800 --> 00:56:22.030
And so to answer your question,
meeting all these chefs--

00:56:22.030 --> 00:56:23.460
it's very surreal.

00:56:23.460 --> 00:56:25.820
Especially in this industry,
where you can actually

00:56:25.820 --> 00:56:30.330
just-- I'm never going to
meet Michael Jordan, probably.

00:56:30.330 --> 00:56:33.601
I'm also not in the NBA.

00:56:33.601 --> 00:56:34.600
But it's the same thing.

00:56:34.600 --> 00:56:36.016
If you're in the
NBA, you probably

00:56:36.016 --> 00:56:37.170
run into these other guys.

00:56:37.170 --> 00:56:41.850
And if you're not mean,
and you're really nice,

00:56:41.850 --> 00:56:45.205
I think that it's
pretty organic.

00:56:45.205 --> 00:56:46.510
And also it's easy for me.

00:56:46.510 --> 00:56:51.010
Because when I was New York,
I wasn't making anything like

00:56:51.010 --> 00:56:56.690
Momofuku or Daniel Boulud or
[? Daniel ?] [? Holm ?] or any

00:56:56.690 --> 00:56:58.080
of the fine dining chefs.

00:56:58.080 --> 00:57:00.980
None of those chefs
were-- it wasn't

00:57:00.980 --> 00:57:02.340
any kind of competitive thing.

00:57:02.340 --> 00:57:06.380
And I came in and gave out as
much free food as possible.

00:57:06.380 --> 00:57:07.520
And I was like, hey guys.

00:57:07.520 --> 00:57:09.320
Here's a bunch of
stuff for your staff.

00:57:09.320 --> 00:57:11.361
I really tried to go into
New York the right way.

00:57:11.361 --> 00:57:14.110
Because I was terrified.

00:57:14.110 --> 00:57:15.930
San Francisco is the
most amazing city

00:57:15.930 --> 00:57:17.520
because everyone is so nice.

00:57:17.520 --> 00:57:19.950
And people kind of
got what we did.

00:57:19.950 --> 00:57:21.990
Because they were here,
along for the ride.

00:57:21.990 --> 00:57:24.072
But a lot of people
don't get what we do.

00:57:24.072 --> 00:57:25.530
People were just
like, oh, the guys

00:57:25.530 --> 00:57:28.590
at that place in the mission
with that other restaurant.

00:57:28.590 --> 00:57:31.230
But in New York, I
was really terrified

00:57:31.230 --> 00:57:33.260
